What is counted? The ČSSD in Prague knows neither Voldemort nor pastry
The new ČSSD councilors in the capital are going to have to overcome, it seems, the obvious language barriers so that the members of the Prague Board and the City Council understand their renewed colleagues from the ODS.
The period Aktuálně.cz &quot;examined&quot; the members of the new ČSSD Council to check their knowledge of the marked slang language that has emerged in recent years in the Council, when the current members of the coalition ruled Prague.
The coded dictionary used by the political cream of Prague during the previous period, by Mayor Pavel Bém, includes some of the most well-known characters, situations and causes of the metropolis.
Surprisingly, it has been found that the new councilors hardly understand these well-known concepts.
At least, that&#39;s what they say.
&quot;Who is Voldemort?&quot;
&quot;The truth is that I do not know.&quot;
&quot;I&#39;m more of a newcomer to Prague politics,&quot; Councilor for Culture Lukáš Kaucký said during the exam on &quot;buddy&quot; terminology.
And as for the veteran politician, Karel Březina reacted the same.
You may be familiar with the concept &quot;golf hole.&quot;
&quot;It&#39;s possibly the only expression of all the ones you asked me that I use from time to time.&quot;
&quot;Otherwise, I don&#39;t normally use slang.&quot;
From the glossary, the definitions of which were published by the newspaper Aktuálně.cz last June before the ODS voting congress, the editorial staff chose six examples, in particular those that are especially related to the Prague municipal authorities.
The socialists had to explain the concepts &quot;Voldemort&quot;, &quot;biggest golf hole in Prague&quot;, &quot;go to the pastry shop&quot;, &quot;bull&#39;s neck&quot;, &quot;betrayal of the capital&quot; and &quot;armour&quot;.
Three councilors agreed to undergo the test and a fourth, Antonín Weinert, who in the future will be responsible for education in Prague, initially agreed, but did not pick up the phone again.
The fifth councilor, Petr Dolínek, directly refused to do so.
&quot;I don&#39;t get involved in these things nor do I intend to value how civic democrats have fun.&quot;
&quot;What does matter to me is how we will understand each other in the execution of our programs,&quot; he said.
As we have seen, councilor Lukáš Kaucký supposedly did not realize that the above title is an expression about an influential businessman and a friend of former mayor Bém, Roman Janoušek.
To Kaucký the word &quot;Voldemort&quot; means nothing; the only term that got it right on the test is &quot;biggest golf hole in Prague&quot;.
&quot;It&#39;s about the Blanka tunnel,&quot; says Kaucký, who immediately adds: &quot;But I rather know about it from the news.&quot;
&quot;I&#39;m going to have to sign up for a language course,&quot; he jokes.
Karel Březina is not the only one who recognizes the Blanka Tunnel in the golf hole, but also the Councilor for the Environment Lukáš Plachý.
Afterwards, both Socio-Democrats know who Voldemort really is and Lukáš Plachý even knows where to find that character; furthermore, he suspects the meaning of &quot;go to the pastry shop&quot;.
&quot;I think it means going to a company in Prague&quot;; Plachý is soon told that this is the headquarters of the Janoušek companies.
Like Březina, he indicates that such knowledge was obtained from the news, but that he does not use such vocabulary.
According to test participants, there is no such familiar glossary of colloquial terms among socio-democrats.
&quot;I asked my companions, but it really seems like we don&#39;t have anything like it.&quot;
&quot;Rather, we use nicknames among ourselves, sometimes abbreviations or puns on names,&quot; says the chairman of the Prague ČSSD, Petr Hulínský, whose party colleagues call Hulda.
&quot;At school they called me Bříza, but I don&#39;t know if my classmates call me that too&quot;, confesses his own nickname Karel Březina.
The newspaper Aktuálně.cz tested the name and it works.
To his fellow party members, Weinert is Děda (similar to &quot;yayo&quot;) or, less friendly, Dědek (&quot;old man&quot;), representative Miroslav Poche, with whom they were associated before the elections in deceptions during party sponsorship, receives the nickname &quot;Igráček&quot; (&quot;playmobil&quot;) by some of his peers.
Nicknames are also the only expressions that Socio Democrats tolerate in party parlance.
Hulínský doesn&#39;t like to be called Hulda, but the newspaper Aktuálně.cz discovered even other nicknames for this Prague president.
&quot;The truncheon rights doctor&quot; seems to remember that Petr Hulínský obtained his doctorate in law at the Bratislava police academy.
The Government wants to limit the torture of &quot;witches&quot;, as published in a brochure
Women considered to be witches in Burkina Faso share certain characteristics.
They are often of advanced age, unable to work, for example for health reasons, single and childless.
Women who &quot;become&quot; witches are sent to an isolated area, so that they do not harm the rest of the town.
&quot;Men seldom suffer such a fate.&quot;
&quot;Healthy young women are not isolated either, because they help with the work and have children,&quot; explains a nun who, in the capital of the West African state of Burkina Faso, takes care of more than a hundred women expelled from their communities in a special residence. .
The local government has decided to oppose this unusual &quot;social measure&quot;.
He issued an informative pamphlet that should help prevent the witch hunt.
However, this has a catch.
&quot;More than 70% of adults in Burkina Faso cannot read,&quot; warns the newspaper Die Standard about the disadvantages of raising awareness in writing.
Witchcraft accusations are also common in other African countries.
In Burkina Faso&#39;s neighboring Ghana, 72-year-old Ammy Hemmah died last week when three women and two men tortured her, covered her in gasoline and burned her.
The news appeared on the BBC.
The authors state that it was due to an unfortunate combination of circumstances.
According to his version, the woman was caught in the oil used for ritual anointing.
It was set on fire when the group wanted to &quot;drive out evil spirits&quot; from the woman.
The isolation of &quot;witches&quot; is supported by people of all educational levels.
The Der Standard newspaper quoted a 42-year-old businessman from Burkina Faso: &quot;Eaters of human souls have always represented a danger,&quot; he said.
While in Burkina Faso the government is trying to appease the witch hunt, in The Gambia last year the president still participated in it.
&quot;The Gambian President Jammeh, following the death of his aunt, launched an extensive hunt for the witches who had allegedly been connected to her death and had attempted to kill the President himself through black magic.&quot;
&quot;To help him, he brought shamans from nearby Guinea who, protected by police, military and the president&#39;s personal escort, forcibly took men and women randomly selected from Gambian villages to the president&#39;s property in Kanilai,&quot; he said in his report the organization Amnesty International.
On the farm, the people arrested had to drink a herbal concoction with hallucinogenic effects, which also caused intestinal and kidney problems.
Two of those arrested did not survive their stay on the farm.
After international pressure, they finally released around a thousand detainees.
Bakala&#39;s tenant: heats himself with coal stoves and signs a higher rent
The man, elderly and tough, walked through the doors of the customer service center of the RPG Byty company of &quot;coal magnate&quot; Zdeňek Bakala, the largest private owner of rental flats in the Czech Republic.
Under his arm he carried some documents with the new rental contracts for three floors: his, his daughter&#39;s and his son&#39;s, who is serving a sentence.
The three of them have just been caught by the liberalization of rents.
Instead of CZK 3,500 a month, the son will pay CZK 4,100 a month from next year for a second-rate two-room apartment with a separate kitchen.
&quot;In addition, it does not have hot water and the heating is based on a solid fuel boiler,&quot; the man shows with his finger in his son&#39;s new contract, over whose signature he has full power.
&quot;But I signed it,&quot; he explains half angry, half resigned.
The civil association BytyOKD.cz, which called the new rental conditions &quot;incorrect and indecent&quot;, advises tenants not to sign the new contracts and to wait until December 7, when it will publish a guide informing how proceed in these cases.
But, before this, the man only makes a gesture.
&quot;Everyone says one thing,&quot; he says with a pout.
Ostrava is becoming a great testing laboratory for liberalization.
After the New Year it will happen with the vast majority of the flats that, in the Czech Republic, were until now under a regulated rent.
Therefore, Aktuálně.cz decided to visit the &quot;laboratory&quot; in person.
The RPG mining lounge is one of four in Ostrava, and by Tuesday at nine it was already full.
Right next to the doors are the security guards and next to them is a machine to take a number.
&quot;Rental 2011&quot; can be read on a luminous button on its touch screen.
When pressed, a piece of paper with a number comes out of the machine.
There is almost no time to even read &quot;157&quot; and the number already appears on the large screen located at the top of the room.
In a second, you&#39;re in the queue.
Soon after, an elderly couple arrives to inquire, but the crowd in the living room is not here because of the new rents.
Most people come to solve regular problems, like in the old days: repair requests, insurance issues and the like.
The letters with the new rental agreements will arrive in Ostrava in the mailboxes of the tenants of most of the 44,000 flats belonging to RPG around mid-November.
RPG Byty proposes in the letters a rent increase of between 15 and 38%.
On November 18, a special window opens at the customer service center for new rentals.
&quot;It&#39;s been running for a week, so it&#39;s just starting,&quot; the workers who are there when the client introduces himself as a journalist respond, after briefly hesitating.
Liberalization and the old flats for Bakala miners are the most sensitive issues in the area.
Before the elections, they were already discussed loud and clear by the Deputy Speaker of Parliament, originally from Ostrava, Lubomír Zaorálek of the ČSSD, and now they appear continuously in the area&#39;s newspapers.
&quot;Twenty years later I want a new floor.&quot;
&quot;They didn&#39;t even change the damn plate in the bathroom,&quot; the man mentioned in the introduction vents.
According to the workers, at the moment mostly retirees come to see if they receive a discount on rent if they sign on time, as RPG&#39;s special offer promises.
Remaining tenants who sign the new lease before December 15 will also receive half of the February rent discount.
However, the mining &quot;liberalization&quot; window undoubtedly fails to dispel the avalanche of doubts.
&quot;Of the 360 customers who were here yesterday, only about forty or fifty people asked about the rent in 2011,&quot; estimates the employee at the window.
Meanwhile, RPG proposes on the web and on its boards to hold individual meetings about contracts when necessary.
If the two parties do not reach an agreement on the rent, the matter must be resolved by an independent judge.
&quot;This is not a threat, but information on the only possible way to proceed and completely in accordance with the law,&quot; warns RPG on its pages.
&quot;No one is going to be judged here,&quot; says one of the RPG Byty employees, and a man who is on the street in front of the customer service center agrees, at least in part, with her.
&quot;I receive a pension of 13,000 and I have 5,000 left for food; I have no means to go to court,&quot; he says.
But, immediately, the employee sows doubt.
&quot;We&#39;ll see&quot;.
&quot;Mr. Zaorálek warns them in the media not to sign, so maybe people will wait,&quot; he says.
Rent regulation will cease to exist in most of the Czech Republic at the beginning of 2011 and, according to RPG Byty, its increase is an economic necessity.
&quot;Current rents still do not even cover the amounts necessary for the maintenance of the community fund,&quot; recalls Pavel Klimeš, director of the residential portfolio of the company RPG Byty, adding that the neglected state of the community fund is angering to tenants is, for landlords, the main reason for raising rent.
While during the five years that elapsed between 2005 and 2010 RPG was able to invest four billion in apartments with rents, in the four years that will go from 2011 to 2014 the figure will increase to 5,200 million.
The large screen hanging from the ceiling, in front of the waiting room seats, now repeats some data that is highlighted in red.
&quot;The rent increase in 2011 by 15% and less applies to 31,200 apartments, that is, more than 90% of RPG properties.&quot;
&quot;In addition, it will always be a maximum of CZK 7.50 per month per square meter,&quot; it says on the screen.
Only increased by 38% the rent of 400 apartments in the RPG portfolio.
&quot;In such cases, it is an increase from extremely low amounts of SEK 19.66 per square meter,&quot; says RPG.
In 2,600 apartments, the rent will remain unchanged next year.
RPG Byty promises that the liberalization will not hit rents all at once, but will escalate between four to eight years.
In addition, it adds the following commitment: the company will invest all the money from the rent increase (see the graph) back into the apartments, mainly in heating savings: new windows and heating.
The people who sign the rent increase agreement will have priority.
Architects have understood that offices also need a nursery
The Avriopoint administrative building in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
No one would say that it also hides a small nursery inside with everything typical of such facilities: colored walls, creative furniture and even a miniature park on the outdoor terrace.
Since October of last year, the children of Arch.Design employees can attend.
The architectural project company Arch.Design, whose studio produced numerous well-known buildings in Brno, thought from the first sketches of the Avriopoint building to include a space for its mini-nursery.
The company employs around 90 people, mainly in the baby boom age, and they wanted to allow architects and draftsmen to return to work soon after maternity leave.
Along with the possibility of enjoying reduced hours, the daycare is one of the benefits that Arch.Design offers its workers within the framework of its social program.
Builders and architects thus have the possibility of combining a demanding profession with childcare.
The mini-nursery was the idea of the Arch.Designu employees themselves and, with the support of management, they managed to obtain funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labor and Social Affairs.
The company&#39;s mini-nursery is financed through the European Social Fund under the Operational Program for Human Resources and Employment, as well as from the state budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to the funding granted (an endowment of more than 2.8 million CZK) they were able to buy the equipment and, after two years, hire qualified personnel and services.
When the funding is exhausted (two years), the company Arch.Design is required to keep the mini-nursery running with its own funds for three years.
The preparation of the project lasted a year and the company Economy Rating contributed to the presentation of the financing request.
Children&#39;s care is in the hands of qualified personnel; In addition, a nurse and a teacher from the Ministry of Education are present all day to care for them. The nursery currently welcomes children with no age limit, although most of them are less than three years old.
Since it is a &quot;mini-nursery&quot;, it can only accommodate a maximum of five children simultaneously, although with shifts more come during the day.
The operation of the crèche is flexible to adapt to the needs of the parents and the children of all the workers have the same right to use the crèche, regardless of the hierarchy within the company.
Although it is individual teaching and care, the contents of the mini-nursery program are comparable to the regular pre-school programme.
In it, children not only play, but also receive quality education: from basic learning to preparing for school, they even teach English.
The class not only has toys and board games, but also a computer for the children.
The presence of small children in the company itself create a friendly and positive atmosphere.
Parents can drop in to see their children at any time and avoid the stress of picking up children late from school when you are away from work.
Thus, parents are more productive while working.
Not surprisingly, this naturally creates a relationship of loyalty between the worker and his employer.
In this way, Arch.Design is among the firm companies that offer a great advantage for the admission of new workers: they support the family and, ultimately, this program reinforced personnel marketing.
The house of bones continues to fascinate after 100 years. Take a look at Gaudí&#39;s interiors
The roof resembles the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs resemble the spine of a dinosaur, and the balconies resemble the open mouth of a fish.
This is the Casa Batlló, in Barcelona, by the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Due to its skeleton-like shape, locals nicknamed it &quot;the house of bones&quot;.
Its organic forms, its striking colours, the novel use of stone, the fragments of tiles and mosaics, a façade reminiscent of scales and the ubiquitous gently curved lines, all of this is typical of Antoni Gaudí&#39;s secession.
The front of the house plays with dreamlike lines, delicate colors and textures taken from nature and fauna.
Paying more attention, one observes a certain geometry, rhythm and a carefully thought out order.
At night, the entire facade of the house looks even more impressive, since it is illuminated in such a way that the brilliance of the colors is enhanced.
It meanders and the torsion of the forms continues to surprise us also inside.
Corrugated wood copies window frames, railings, door trims, peepholes, and signs.
Casa Batlló, which is located in the Eixample neighborhood at number 43 of the lively shopping street of Passeig de Grácia, arose from the remodeling of a house from 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction lasted two years and the house was completed in the year 1906.
The investor, wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, initially insisted on tearing down the previous building and starting from scratch, but soon accepted Gaudí&#39;s idea of a cheaper and novel reconstruction.
However, Casa Batlló, made up of various apartments, was not designed by Antoni Gaudí alone.
The architect Josep María Jujol collaborated in the design.
In fact, in his plans for the project, decorations for the representative apartment of the owner of the property and the mosaics used on the facade arose.
Other creators and artists also work on the façade.
Collaboration in the Casa Batlló proposals was the beginning of Jujol&#39;s successful collaboration with Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of Gaudí&#39;s Casa Milá and Park Güell, where other parts of it are located.
Due to its organic shape, locals soon after its completion nicknamed it &quot;the house of bones&quot;.
Others, due to the specific mechanism for opening the windows, began to call it &quot;the house of yawns&quot;.
It is also said that, at the top of the construction, the sword of Saint George, patron saint of Catalonia, appears.
Other sculptural elements of the construction hide religious motives.
Gaudí designed a unique central heating system for the house with ventilation vents and typical chimneys.
Its forty-five degree inclination may seem strange.
During construction, Gaudí did not respect the construction regulations of the time at all and was not influenced by them.
Even so, the construction obtained the corresponding permit from the beginning, although obviously the data indicated in it on the planned reconstruction were so vague that, two years later, upon its completion, the city council was so shocked by the result that they asked that it be corrected
It bothered him, for example, that the construction included columns even up to the public sidewalk.
The arrangements were never made, quite the contrary: just fifteen days after the council&#39;s request, Josep Batlló requested (and obtained) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
The owner himself settled on the lower floors.
On the gallery on the second floor was the living room and on the third floor the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The six-story house is completely crossed by a staircase that leads to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform consisted of breaking all the angles and straight lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of connection of space.
The common part can be fully connected by opening the doors of the rooms and a larger group can communicate in this way without problems, without giving up the privacy necessary for more intimate conversations.
The house, with Gaudí&#39;s reconstruction, not only got a new façade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaudí plays with light, white and blue tiles that cover the interior patio and skylights.
The game with the two colors provides maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was simply based on the principle that white reflects more light than dark colours, which instead absorb the sun&#39;s rays.
Anyone can visit Casa Batlló, which in 2005 was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and ornate apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
With the visits they confirmed, or discovered, that it is a very profitable business and they expanded the visits to the common area and the attic, including the roof terrace.
The entrance fee to the monument is not negligible, it reaches 16.50 euros, although students, pensioners and holders of tourist cards get a 20% discount.
The amount considerably exceeds the price of the entrance of other Gaudí constructions in the city.
