How to choose the mattress and box spring: women and men look for different things
No pompous bed frame; What really gives a good bed its quality is the surface to lie on, that is, the mattress and the box spring.
Above all, they must complement each other perfectly so that they adapt to the specific users.
Numerous elements come into play during the choice, including the owner&#39;s weight, height, state of health, and gender.
The type of interior in which the mattress and box spring are located is also important.
A typical example?
For example, in a weekend cabin that does not usually have heating, latex mattresses should not be used because they &quot;warm up&quot; more slowly.
In addition, they usually weigh considerably more than the usual polyurethane mattresses.
Consequently, it is necessary to turn them over more frequently.
If the channels in the center are not properly aerated and, above, are on a firm base, they keep moisture inside. Mold may even appear underneath.
When choosing a bed, customs also influence.
Anyone who has spent a lot of time abroad often uses a very high mattress with a soft layer and will have trouble feeling comfortable on a lower, harder surface.
&quot;Almost every hockey player who came back from the NHL complained that they didn&#39;t sleep as well here.&quot;
&quot;For their crushed shoulders, heels and hips they needed mattresses with a soft layer of memory foam.&quot;
&quot;This type of mattress is also recommended for people with diabetes who have nervous system problems, so they receive poor information from the joints and the skin,&quot; explains Sylva Hadamcziková, who specializes in padded furniture.
Many hockey players, like other customers, have long preferred memory foam mattresses.
&quot;Today there is no problem anymore, because they have these suitable Tempur and the Italian Magniflex, but also the Czech brand Tropico.&quot;
You no longer have to be an NHL player to appreciate memory foam.
This &quot;miracle&quot; works in a very simple way.
It optimizes its rigidity and shape based on the heat absorbed or adapts to your body heat.
Nothing exerts pressure; During the night, it won&#39;t spin like after a hard game.
You just sleep better.
The memory foam also works as protection against sores.
When choosing the size of the mattress, add the length of your feet to its height, that is, between 21 and 34 cm.
A man or woman with a height of around 180 cm will need a bed between 210 and 220 cm.
The minimum width for one person should be, in a double room, 90 cm, in total 180 cm.
In the case of single rooms, for example single rooms, a minimum of 120 to 140 cm is recommended.
So that a possible visitor is also comfortable.
&quot;If not, a simple rule of thumb can be applied to calculate the width: when lying on your back, you should have your hands comfortably tucked in towards the elbows,&quot; advises engineer Helena Prokopová, an expert at Cechu čalouníků a dekoratérů, who has been in the field for many years. of the problem of healthy sleep and the ergonomics of furniture, a subject that he teaches in specialized schools.
In double rooms, everyone needs their own box spring and mattress, so during the purchase you have to pay attention to match the height of the mattresses.
Otherwise, it will be necessary to mount the bed bases at different heights, which is not always possible in all beds.
Foam mattresses should have a minimum height of 14cm, innerspring models a minimum of 15cm, of which at least 3cm is for the form-fitting and softening layer.
&quot;When touching it with your hand or sitting on the mattress, the springs should certainly not be noticeable,&quot; warns Helena Prokopová.
Each mattress requires a certain type of box spring.
Fully padded bedrooms, in which the mattress and base are like Siamese twins, do not make sense in the bedroom.
Mattresses breathe badly and you can&#39;t wash their cover, which is often done today.
And, since we perspire between 0.2 and 0.75 liters of sweat each night, it&#39;s clear that after about five or seven years the mattress will begin to remind us of a large (and congested) sieve.
For this reason, specialists reject slogans that speak of a mattress life of up to 25 years or even a lifetime guarantee.
However, everything has a but.
Therefore, sellers give advice: on mattresses with a width of 120 or 140 cm, take care of cleaning and washing the cover carefully, but better add a mattress protector that can be easily removed and washed.
Although mattress covers are currently manufactured with a zipper around their entire perimeter, so when they are opened they remain in two parts (something very important for washing and the size of the washing machine!), their handling in larger models size (and by a single person) lifting the mattress can seem like a fight between a flyweight and a heavyweight.
In bed, instead of a box spring, do you have a firm board?
Never!
At most for beds designed for visitors to spend one night.
However, you must (if you don&#39;t already have them) make ventilation holes in the board and must be used with a mattress with inner springs and a minimum height of 15 cm with pocketed springs (such as German Taschenfederkern) and a layer soft.
Polyurethane mattresses should not be used on such bases.
For non-adjustable slatted beds containing between 14 and 18 slats, latex mattresses or sandwich mattresses (for example, a combination of latex and coconut fiber) can be used, although a bed base with a higher number of slats is always better. sheets, 28 or more, in which the sheets of the lower back are reinforced and their rigidity can be regulated.
Adjustable slatted bases should not be used with a spring mattress, as it does not react to recline.
In addition to slat stiffness adjustment, the shoulder protection can also be used.
It is a special fixation of the sheets that allows you to press or even tilt the sheets in such a way that they perfectly &quot;surround&quot; the shoulders during sleep.
For men with very broad shoulders, this is very important.
They are even remembered by mattress manufacturers who, in the &quot;masculine&quot; ones, began to use a softer area precisely around the shoulders.
They also remember women, for whom they put a softer area around the hips.
For the most demanding customers, there are bed bases with a cross or slat structure with the so-called multi-torque damping.
The pressure is distributed between different points and the tension is lowered.
You should also keep in mind that even if you use the right mattress and box spring, if you use a bad (big and &quot;fluffy&quot;) pillow, most of the benefits will be lost.
The basic rule is simple: the pillow must support the head and the corners can only reach up to the shoulders, so that the muscles can relax.
The recommended suitable size is 50 x 60 cm, something normal for example in Scandinavia.
When lying on your side, the pillow should be at the same level (when combined with the shoulder bolster or the softest area of the mattress) as your shoulder height.
Modern mattresses have something to do, it seems, with the original straw-filled mattresses.
Manufacturers continue to use, more and more often, natural materials or, at least, mixtures.
In fact, biological mattresses are in fashion.
Petroleum-based raw materials, from which polyurethane foam is made, are filled with natural oils, for example castor or soybean.
In fact, virtually all known manufacturers use soy.
&quot;Organic, in the case of mattresses, means that the core is made only of materials of natural origin,&quot; explains Petr Vašíček from the company Tropico Plus.
Likewise, natural substances are used during the manufacture of the mattress cover, one of the first aloe vera.
But you can also opt for microcapsules, which release a fresh scent of forest or lavender.
There are also differences for men and women.
While men &quot;cool&quot; with plant extracts from the breeze, so that the mattress cover absorbs heat and cools the body, women prefer to &quot;warm&quot; the cover.
Red pepper extract improves blood circulation, so that women feel more warmth.
Current favourites?
Mattresses made of cold foam, which are more porous, with an adapted cell structure, which makes them more permeable than normal polyurethane and offers more permeability.
The combination of different stiffnesses of cold and viscoelastic foam allows us to manufacture mattresses with different zones that know exactly where the head, shoulders and heels go.
A good quality mattress will cost you seven thousand crowns and up.
Those that perform a therapeutic function usually have a lower VAT, since they are considered as sanitary means.
The first to gain this advantage in the Czech Republic was Gumotex.
It is difficult to save on mattresses and box springs.
Sometimes you can approve offers from manufacturers or sellers, who sometimes offer two mattresses for the price of one.
For example, the Magniflex brand offers Duofreeze mattresses with Memory foam attached to the cover for SEK 11,990.
The second is obtained for free.
The era of memory foam with an open cell structure and high density began with the &quot;cosmic&quot; material from Tempur.
Initially it emerged as a material for NASA, because during takeoffs the astronauts were subjected to an enormous overload.
Tempur softens in the heat and hardens in the cold.
Consequently, the warm human body exerts a perfect effect and optimally adapts its pressure.
Therefore, it is ideal to prevent sores from occurring, but also to improve comfort during sleep.
Memory foam is not only used in mattresses, but also for sanitary products, for example for pillows that are placed under the legs and provide relief and circulation.
Domestic manufacturers, for example, use Eucatherm C or Twinsaver foam and the like.
More and more parents use people tracking devices to control their children
Fear for their children leads more and more people to think about controlling them by GPS.
The system, initially intended for vehicle tracking, can also track the movement of people and thus contribute, for example, in cases such as the disappearance of the nine-year-old girl Anička Janatková.
At the moment the device is about the size of a matchbox, but it will soon shrink to the size of a watch.
Many people were scared by the case of the missing Anička and they began to report on the means available to better protect their children.
Even at the cost of invading your privacy.
&quot;We are all trying to tell ourselves that this is not spying, but another way to reduce the chances of a tragedy,&quot; says Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the providers of tracking devices on the Czech market.
&quot;I recognize that in certain cases such devices can be abused, for example if they get into someone&#39;s bag without their knowledge, but we haven&#39;t come across such cases yet.&quot;
&quot;Most customers really buy it for security reasons,&quot; adds Pilin.
In his opinion, children should always know what the &quot;little box&quot; is for and how to use it in an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bočková warns against the fact that if the child does not want to take it, he will simply throw it away.
&quot;Even the youngest children show great creativity in intentionally losing certain things if they want to avoid being controlled.&quot;
&quot;Before, parents relied heavily on cell phones, but they could be turned off just as easily as the tracking device,&quot; says Bočková.
In his opinion, it is debatable whether such a device is really useful in the event of an attack.
&quot;If it&#39;s a staged kidnapping, the perpetrator will almost always check to see if the child is carrying some sort of electronic device that could give away their location.&quot;
&quot;Now it&#39;s the phone.&quot;
&quot;As the use of tracking devices becomes more widespread, you will also be looking for them, since their sale will undoubtedly be carried out with a lot of publicity.&quot;
&quot;In such cases, criminals are always one step ahead of the police,&quot; says the psychologist.
However, he adds that such devices can help in the event of an impromptu attack by a pedophile.
According to Robert Čech from the company RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services for both vehicles and people, even if the tracking device is immediately destroyed after an attack, its presence can help.
&quot;You can configure the device to regularly send the position after a certain period.&quot;
&quot;If it takes damage, it will at least make the last position of the person in question easier.&quot;
“More expensive devices have a built-in tilt meter, so if the person simply slips and freezes, the device will immediately issue a warning with the position in question,” Čech says.
In his opinion, such a service can be obtained even with smartphones with navigation, where only special software has to be installed.
The problem with current tracking units is that at the moment they are about matchbox-sized devices or the smallest mobile phones.
Therefore, they can be lost.
According to Macro Weil&#39;s Pilin, that&#39;s why tests are currently underway with devices that look like a digital watch.
&quot;In addition, they will have the added advantage that a potential attacker may not identify the device.&quot;
&quot;Or that it identifies it after a certain time, which can save the police time,&quot; he adds.
Whether the tracking devices are worn on the wrist or dangling, they will still use the same technology used for vehicle tracking.
This is position checking with a GPS system (used in normal car navigation) combined with the function of a mobile phone that communicates the current position.
The army has enough matchlocks to encircle the whole of the Czech Republic. But they only last two years
The Czech army bought 445 kilometers of fuse to ignite explosives.
Already last year the Ministry of Defense added 224 kilometers of fuse to its arsenal.
Therefore, they have stocks for 225 years.
The problem is that the useful life of the wick is two years, four at the most.
The army bought the fuse for explosives from the STV Group, as for forty million crowns.
The General&#39;s staff responded to MF DNES justifying the purchase of such a huge amount of match by saying that soldiers need 60 kilometers of match per year for training maneuvers.
According to the calculations of the army pyrotechnicians, with whom MF DNES contacted, it is nevertheless decided that, in such a case, such maneuvers with frequent use of explosives should be carried out every year also by all generals, high command officers, and even secretaries and cleaners.
They wanted defense minister Alexandr Vondr and army captain Vlastimil Picek exempted.
Only in this way could it be justified that the army spends sixty kilometers of fuse.
Such a length is equivalent to 25,000 explosions.
Even if it did, the army would have enough supplies to last more than ten years.
If, on the contrary, as the experts say, for the initial training of each new professional he arrives with a maximum of two meters of fuse, the army would have with the new purchase (even adding the consumption of engineer or special units) sufficient stocks for the 225 indicated above.
The soldiers of the rapid intervention brigade recently complained personally to Minister Vondra because they say that they have little ammunition for various weapons, so even shooting practice is limited for money.
And let&#39;s not talk about the lack of underwear.
&quot;I also fail to understand how they repeatedly buy such amounts of wick from us.&quot;
&quot;But it&#39;s their decision, and they will certainly know why they are acting this way.&quot;
&quot;For us, the military is a good customer that we as a company try to satisfy,&quot; admits STV Group Sales Director Jan Děcký.
Defense Ministry spokesman Jan Pejšek defends the hundreds of kilometers of fuse, also saying that he will have stocks of this &quot;ammunition&quot; for at least ten years.
However, Jan Děcký from STV Group points out that the fuse only has a useful life of four years and, in the case of pyrotechnic products for the army or police, two years.
&quot;If it is stored in perfect conditions, it can last up to four,&quot; says one of the soldiers who, due to possible criticism from the army, does not want to give his name.
After the end of its useful life, each ammunition must be carefully checked to see if it is still reliable and will not harm soldiers.
But these tests are not free and require additional investment.
Another argument of the Ministry is that, when buying 445 kilometers of fuse, it obtained a discount.
&quot;They cost us 60% less than last year&#39;s order of 244 kilometers,&quot; says Pejšek, a spokesman for the Defense Ministry&#39;s purchasing center.
Just to compare: the annual consumption of fuses by police pyrotechnicians, who dispose of ammunition from the Second World War or that left by the Soviet army, has not exceeded 1,500 meters for years.
In addition, the police always ask for just enough to deplete the ammunition before its useful life ends.
They decided this for safety reasons for the pyrotechnicians and, in addition, more modern and reliable types of fuse can be obtained in the meantime.
The Ministry is already clearly struggling to finish tens of thousands of tons of ammunition from the Warsaw Pact era, when the 200,000-strong Czechoslovak army was preparing for a campaign on the Rhine.
According to the pyrotechnicians with whom MF DNES spoke, after a couple of years the following problem will occur with the current one: hundreds of kilometers of old fuse will have to be removed, which is now being bought &quot;cheap&quot;.
Until now I continue living from the contacts I got thanks to the contest
