A survey that reveals the ridiculous rules
The Absurdez survey of the year is part of the business tournament for the fourth time.
It has already managed to remove some ridiculous rules.
The unknown winner of the new edition of the Absurdez poll of the year was the obligation to bring to the administration documents that officials can access online.
The decision was made by more than a third of the nearly 4,000 voters.
For example, the Social Security Administration required an extract from the business register, although its officials can obtain it with two mouse movements.
Thanks to the survey, this has changed.
&quot;The Czech social security administration will no longer ask for an extract from the company register when it checks the insured&#39;s deposits,&quot; said ČSSZ spokeswoman Jana Buraňová.
The objective of the Absurdity of the Year survey is to consult the rules and regulations that companies and entrepreneurs in the Czech Republic must respect and to try to eliminate those that are absurd.
This year, for the fourth time, it is part of the business tournament of the publication Hospodářské noviny and is beginning to create fans among the general public as well.
While last year&#39;s edition had the participation of three thousand voters, this year it practically reached four thousand.
Not surprisingly, since we still have plenty of various legal obligations that need to be followed just to trade.
&quot;Perhaps we are first in the world in terms of the number of papers required for tax returns,&quot; says Karel Havlíček from the Association of Small and Medium-Sized Businesses and Entrepreneurs in the Czech Republic.
Simplification of business rules has been a stated goal of all governments for years.
However, compared to the rest of the world, the situation is improving especially in the Czech Republic.
According to the World Bank, from the point of view of the conditions for having a company, the Czech Republic is in 74th position, that is, eight places worse than last year.
The Absurdity of the Year contest was held for the first time in 2006 and is repeated every year in the same way.
Anyone can indicate some administrative or bureaucratic absurdity every year between April and the end of September, when the contest closes.
Proposals can be made on the website www.firmaroku.cz. The contest organizer then chooses seven candidates for the &quot;anti-prize&quot; and, during October, allows the public to vote online via www.firmaroku.cz/absurdita and www.ihned.cz.
The absurdity that receives the most votes wins.
More than a hundred submitted for this year&#39;s survey, including 105 rules and regulations that don&#39;t make sense.
The examples were submitted by both businessmen, professional associations and journalists.
Among the &quot;finalists&quot; of the contest was, for example, the requirement that vehicles for the maintenance of roads and highways pay the toll or that businessmen with twenty employees, two offices and two bathrooms paint the walls every two years.
The list of this year&#39;s seventy proposals is published on the contest pages.
The announcement of the contest, which always takes place at the beginning of November in Wenceslas Square in Prague, is part of an event in which personalities from the political and social world usually participate.
This year, for example, this event was attended by Eva Svobodová, director of the Association of small and medium-sized companies and entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic, or Petr Kužel, president of the Chamber of Commerce of the Republic.
&quot;Economic prosperity cannot be maintained if the State continually hinders businessmen, which is why my goal is to eliminate a minimum of thirty paragraphs each year that currently unnecessarily complicate trade&quot;, announced the Minister of Industry and Commerce Martin Kocourek .
Efforts to eliminate absurd regulations do not remain in borage water.
In 2007, what bothered people the most was the employer&#39;s obligation to notify the business office in the area of permanent operation three days in advance of the intention to attend a fair or exhibition with a position.
This obligation was eliminated in the new industrial law.
The obligation that finished second in number of votes in 2007, that is, the communication to the labor office by its foreign workers of work trips of up to 30 days, was eliminated in the law of the so-called green card .
And the third time is the charm.
The Absurdity of the year 2009 was the regulation for physiotherapists to have a large mirror, a fridge and two floor scales in their office.
For this reason, this year the Ministry of Health issued a communication saying that it had eliminated the obligation to have a refrigerator.
