Families will have to pay additional expenses of several hundred crowns per month
Households will have to pay from January not only for all types of energy, but also for water and electricity, heating supplements and, in some cases, higher rents.
As a result, families will have to take several hundred crowns a month more out of their wallets from January than now.
The price of electricity increases by 4.6%, gas by around 2%, in some cities they will have to pay up to 10% more for water supply and many also increase the price of central heating.
The increase in electricity for families living in apartments should amount to about 100 kroner more per year than now.
However, the main electricity providers reduced prices, as support for the production of energy from renewable sources, particularly photovoltaics, has increased.
However, gas becomes moderately more expensive, especially at a time when heating is used the most and, therefore, the consumption is higher.
In this case, they must also count on a couple of hundred crowns more per year.
As electricity and gas become more expensive across the country, the price change for central heating varies from place to place.
The price increase is mainly planned by the largest municipality.
For example, households in Pardubice or Hradec Králové will pay an additional 50 SEK per month for central heating from January, while families in Liberec will pay more than 1,000 additional SEK per year.
Residents in Prague will also have to bear a 9% increase in the price of water and heating, especially in case the city increases the rent for infrastructure.
If the rent does not change, Praguers will pay an additional 6.8%.
Prices in Prague, however, will still be among the lowest in the entire country.
In northern Bohemia, where current prices are among the highest, both rates will become more expensive by 7.4%.
The rental prices of 450,000 rented flats in Prague, where the regulation will end in January, may rise considerably.
For example, the company CPI Byty, which owns around 2,500 flats in Ústí nad Labem, will increase the rent from January by up to 100%.
The company will take those who disagree with the new lease to court.
Regulated rents, which benefit the residents of around 300,000 apartments, could increase next year by up to 10%.
Czech youths get drunk on Fernet and rum. The beer is no longer in mode, because it takes effect slowly
Fernet, rum, vodka and even good whiskeys stolen from their parents.
Those are the drinks that lead to young drinkers under the age of fifteen ending up in medical care.
Children who end up lying in the hospital all the time to get over a hangover are no longer an exception.
This stems from the experience of physicians encountering such cases on hospital pediatric admissions.
&quot;Drinking beer or wine is not in fashion anymore, because they take a long time to get drunk.&quot;
&quot;Now the fashion is strong alcoholic beverages,&quot; Luděk Pelikán, head of paediatrics at the Hořovice Hospital in central Bohemia, tells Právo.
&quot;When they manage to grab a bottle from their father out of the cupboard, it may be whiskey, but usually it&#39;s Fernet and vodka.&quot;
&quot;Vodka has the advantage that it lightens up with juice and doesn&#39;t smell as much,&quot; he explains.
This is also confirmed by the spokesperson for the Motol University Hospital, Eva Jurinová.
&quot;Normally, it&#39;s usually Fernet or rum.&quot;
&quot;Those are modern spirits, particularly among schoolchildren.&quot;
&quot;In some cases, they use brandy they took at home,&quot; adds Jurinová.
According to Chief Pelikán, thirteen and fourteen-year-old drinkers are the ones who usually appear in hospitals.
Before Hořovice, where she has been working since this year, she worked for a decade in pediatrics in Motol, where ambulances brought young people from nearby areas.
&quot;One girl had to enter maybe four times.&quot;
&quot;It started at the age of twelve, when they brought her in with 3.5 alcohol in her blood, in addition to a mixture with ecstasy,&quot; says the department&#39;s doctor about this case.
&quot;He was at the Holešovice fair at some dance party.&quot;
&quot;The interesting thing is that her mother wasn&#39;t even surprised that her daughter disappeared for 48 hours,&quot; the boss is surprised.
It is precisely the lack of interest of parents or even their clear tolerance towards drinking by their children that is considered the main cause of the increase in alcohol consumption among young people.
Experts point out that, in the case of children, one cannot properly speak of dependency.
&quot;An alcoholic is understood to be a person who has been chronically dependent on alcohol for several years, with all the phenomena associated with it, which does not occur in children.&quot;
&quot;In those who drink alcohol repeatedly, it is rather due to a systematically failed social or family environment,&quot; explains Chief Pelikán.
According to the spokeswoman Jurinová, this year at the Motol pediatric clinic, forty drunken children were hospitalized until mid-November.
However, the statistics only show those who come with severe poisoning and must remain in the hospital.
Young drinkers who, after a mobile medical examination, go home with their parents or with the police, do not count.
In addition to the cases in which the children simply gather after school and drink brandy, for Pelikán there are three seasonal highs and lows that are worth mentioning: Halloween, New Year&#39;s Eve and the end of the school year.
&quot;In such a circumstance, they drink because of bad grades or, on the contrary, they celebrate the start of the holidays.&quot;
&quot;On the day of the witches I have come to see up to seven drunk children at the same time in admissions,&quot; adds Pelikán.
Drinkers who spend the night in detox under the supervision of doctors, paradoxically, have the advantage of not having a terrible hangover at home the next day.
The morning headache, caused by dehydration and lack of glucose, is avoided with the injection of a serum with glucose and with the nutrients that the body lacks.
&quot;These take it much better, because after the hectic night, they get up well and do not hurt at all.&quot;
&quot;They&#39;re just confused about where they are,&quot; says Pelikán, adding that patients often lose their good humor, at least when they see the expenses they&#39;ve incurred.
Transfer by ambulance and hospitalization in a critically ill room can cost tens of thousands of crowns.
&quot;I have often used the cost as a means of educating them, when I visit to tell the children directly how much their drunkenness has cost and that they would have to spend the whole summer in a youth job for you to earn enough to pay for that night. Pelikan adds.
Health insurance, in his opinion perhaps as a regressive measure, which usually reimburses people for treatment costs, does not do so in the case of children who drink.
Two L-159 aircraft are found for the first time in foreign hands in Spain
Two L-159 planes out of a total of five, for which the Czech Ministry of Defense replaced the Casa C-295M plane, left on Tuesday for Seville, where the manufacturer of the Casa aircraft - EADS is located.
It is the first time that such a device has been in the hands of anyone other than the Czech military.
At the moment, they were only abroad for practice or demonstration flights.
It is the two-seater version L-159T1, which until now was used by the Czech army and was still airworthy.
The three remaining aircraft are single-seater L-159.
These are still kept at Aer Vodochody and the intermediary for the sale, the Omnipol company, already took charge of them last week.
Jan Peješk, from the defense press department, indicates that it is not yet known when the planes will be physically withdrawn from Vodochody.
&quot;The single-seater L-159 planes, on the other hand, were separated from the planes that had been repaired a long time ago, without additional investments or contributions from the Ministry.&quot;
&quot;The L-159T1 two-seaters were exchanged in their current state,&quot; he told Právo Pejšek.
He added that the army does not run out of two-seater aircraft, since in May 2009 the army signed a contract with Aer Vodochody in the amount of 200 million crowns for the construction of four unnecessary L-159 devices for two-seaters.
One of the new planes was already received by the army in July, the other will be delivered at the end of the year.
According to Pejšek, EADS has promised that the aircraft will be added to the equipment of some allied countries.
&quot;In the contract it is clearly indicated that the EADS company is the one that withdraws the L-159 aircraft and that they will be used for the training of pilots from NATO countries.&quot;
&quot;Therefore, it is up to the buyer to decide how they are going to use them in this framework,&quot; says Pejšek.
The newspaper Hospodářské noviny published ahead of time that, for example, the Spanish army is not interested in L-159s.
The exchange of five L-159s for a Casa plane and the purchase of three other aircraft for 3.5 billion crowns were approved last year by the government of Mirek Topolánek.
The Ministry of Defense did not call a tender for the purchase and negotiated directly with EADS.
The current defense leadership claims that the exchange promotes the future export of L-159 abroad.
The Czech army acquired 72 aircraft from Aer and only uses 24, so it wants to sell the rest.
The purchase of Casa aircraft may possibly have legal consequences.
