A longer index finger than the ring finger indicates a lower risk of cancer
Men who have the index finger longer than the ring finger are subject to a lower risk of prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published Wednesday in a British cancer journal.
It could depend on the level of testosterone, the male hormone.
&quot;Our results indicate that relative finger length may be a simple test of prostate cancer risk, particularly for men up to age 60,&quot; said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Research on cancer at the University of Warwick.
Therefore, the finger could help determine which men should be tested for prostate cancer, particularly if prostate cancer is associated with genetic risk or other detrimental factors, such as family health problems, Eeles says.
During the period 1994-2009, he followed up with a British counterpart more than 1,500 patients with prostate cancer and, simultaneously, 3,000 healthy men.
More than half of the study participants had the index finger of the right hand shorter than the ring finger.
They were just as likely to have prostate cancer as 19% of those whose fingers were the same length.
In the case of men with an index finger longer than the ring finger, this risk was reduced by 33%; for men aged less than 60% the reduction reached 87%.
The relationship between the length of the two fingers in question, determined in the prenatal period, reflects different levels of hormones to which the fetus is exposed in the womb.
A lower testosterone level corresponds to a longer index.
Previous studies indicated that testosterone influences the development of prostate cancer.
The great Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, Professor Václav Pačes, told ČTK that he is aware of the study, but does not think that the relationship between finger length and cancer can be &quot;fully proven&quot;.
