the democratic routine
Support for democracy in Latin America continues to rise, as does support for private business.
Crime is a bigger concern than unemployment.
Furthermore, in much of the region, Brazil is seen as a more influential country than the United States.
These are some of the conclusions of the latest Latinobarómetro survey carried out in 18 countries and published exclusively by The Economist.
Since the survey has been carried out regularly since 1995, it makes it possible to monitor changes in attitudes in the region.
Two related issues stand out in the results of this year&#39;s survey, conducted in September and early October.
The first is the relatively lively humor prevailing in Latin America.
The second is the increasing stability of attitudes towards democracy and its main institutions.
Support for democracy has increased considerably in several countries on the Pacific coast of South America (see table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has averaged 6% a year since 2002, support for democracy has risen from a low 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
It also grew in Mexico, where the economy has recovered after suffering a large drop in production last year.
However, only half of those surveyed in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous countries in the area, are convinced Democrats, which lowers the regional average (see graph 2).
Some 44% of those surveyed in the region declared themselves satisfied with the way democracy works in practice in their country, the same figure as last year, but considerably higher than the 25% registered in 2001 (figure 3).
Some 34% stated that they trusted their country&#39;s Congress and 45% their government, the same number as last year in both cases, but considerably higher than in 2003 (17% and 24%, respectively).
A decade ago, the economic turmoil in Latin America severely affected support for democracy.
The fact that it has held up during the global financial crisis is probably due to the fact that many Latin American countries were only affected by a brief recession and enjoyed a strong recovery.
In addition, the existence of a stronger social safety net has helped protect the poorest.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty increased only marginally in 2009 and has fallen again this year, to 32%.)
However, the mood varies considerably from country to country (see graph 4).
Brazil&#39;s good economic performances and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, is reflected in a general feeling of progress.
Such sentiment is less common in Mexico and Central America, where the recession was most severe and violent crime has increased.
For the second time since the surveys began, more respondents in Latin America cite crime, rather than unemployment, as the most serious problem facing their country (see chart 5).
Some 31% say that either they or a close relative have been a victim of crime in the last year, a figure that is down from 38% last year and the lowest percentage since 1995.
The more positive economic performance is reflected in greater support for private companies and the market economy: around 71% of those surveyed in the region affirm that private companies are indispensable for development, while in 2007 it was only the 56% (see graph 6).
Some 58% agree that the market economy is the only system that will allow their country to develop, up from 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of those polled in Venezuela feel the same way (and 80% support private companies), even though its leftist president, Hugo Chávez, is expropriating many private companies.
Brazil is the country that exercises the greatest leadership in the region, as indicated by 19% of respondents (compared to 18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, the same figure as last year) and Venezuela (9% compared to 11% a year ago).
However, the United States is the country considered most influential by respondents in Mexico and much of Central America, while Venezuela holds that title in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
trash elections
No one expected the November 28 general elections in Haiti to be perfect.
However, they went much worse than foreigners trying to help the country recover from its problems feared.
Votes were put into the ballot box, some people voted several times, ballots thrown into the sewers, polling stations destroyed and acts of intimidation.
Polling stations opened hours late.
Many Haitians, including groups displaced by the January earthquake, were wandering the area trying to figure out where to vote.
Some of them, in the end, gave up.
A dozen presidential candidates, including several of the most popular, denounced fraud and called for the annulment of the elections.
Protests, some of them violent, spread across the country.
However, Edmond Mulet, the senior United Nations official in Haiti, declared that it was &quot;a relatively good election in many ways.&quot;
Observers from the Organization of American States and the Caribbean Community cautiously stated that &quot;we do not believe that these irregularities, however serious they may be, necessarily invalidate the process.&quot;
In other words, the show goes on.
The electoral authority, which opponents say is committed to René Préval, the unpopular outgoing president, and his candidate, Jude Célestin, is due to announce preliminary results on December 7.
The tiebreaker is expected to take place in January.
All hope regarding the elections has not yet been lost.
The two main opposition candidates, Michel Martelly, a rapper, and Mirlande Manigat, a former first lady, have withdrawn their initial petition calling for the invalidation of the vote.
But problems can still arise if the electoral authority declares that Mr. Célestin, who has little if any support, has moved on to the second round.
With the cholera epidemic sweeping the country and more than a million earthquake survivors still living in tents, strong abstention is expected.
When the time came, many Haitians wanted to vote, but were unable to do so due to a lack of organization.
Around 250,000 identity documents, necessary to vote, had not yet been distributed shortly before the elections.
The stakes are high.
Aid donors view the election of a popular and legitimate government as an essential step in rebuilding Haiti.
And, as has become clear, Haitians themselves think so too.
Tiptoeing towards the center
In the weeks that have passed since she lost her husband, Cristina Fernández, the president of Argentina, has enjoyed great sympathy among the public that has increased her popularity rating by 20 points, to more than 50%, the highest level that he has registered since his election in 2007.
Regardless, whether she can turn it into a successful campaign for a second term in next year&#39;s elections will depend on whether the clearly affected Mrs. Fernández puts aside the intransigence of her late husband, her predecessor and political partner, Néstor Kirchner.
And, at this point, the indications are not conclusive.
Mr. Kirchner, who continued to run economic policy even after his wife succeeded him as president, had a habit of drawing up budgets that underestimated tax revenue, economic growth and inflation.
This allowed the presidential couple to spend the additional income at their discretion.
In theory, Mrs. Fernández&#39;s government lost its majority in Congress last year.
However, the opposition is divided, a situation that has worsened after Kirchner&#39;s death of a heart attack on October 27.
Some dissenting members of the ruling Peronist movement have confronted Mrs. Fernández.
However, after chaotic sessions in which one deputy punched another in the face and other deputies accused the government of bribery, Congress decided to reject the 2011 budget.
&quot;I&#39;m not going to argue,&quot; said the president.
Consequently, the 2010 budget will be applied to the following year, which will offer the president even greater leeway when it comes to spending it.
The economy is improving considerably: it will probably grow as much as 9% this year.
The official inflation rate is currently at 11.1%, but numerous private estimates, as well as union wage demands, put it near 30%.
Mr Kirchner, who came to power in 2003 when Argentina was on the verge of economic collapse, made growth and poverty reduction his priorities, rather than controlling inflation.
He refused to negotiate with the IMF, put pressure on the private sector and made INDEC, the statistics institute, adapt the official inflation statistics.
Will President Fernández now moderate these policies?
He has called meetings between the private sector and union leaders.
In addition, its officials say they want to limit salary increases next year to 18%.
The economy has been boosted by the high prices of Argentine agricultural exports in the world.
However, inflation has limited the boost to growth achieved with a large devaluation in 2002.
Perhaps for this reason Mrs. Fernández is showing signs of wanting to restore Argentina&#39;s financial ties with the rest of the world.
Earlier in the year, the government reached an agreement with bondholders who had refused a previous forced restructuring of debt that Argentina had failed to pay in 2001.
At present, it seems that Mrs. Fernández is about to enter into an agreement with the creditor governments grouped in the Paris Club, to which she owes around 6.7 billion dollars.
The Kirchners always insisted that this would not involve IMF supervision, as is customary.
However, last month Amado Boudou, the Minister of Economy, announced that the Fund will offer &quot;technical assistance&quot; to develop a new national consumer price index, which seems like a prelude to cleaning up INDEC.
It is not clear if President Fernández wants to continue in politics when her term ends, taking into account that she no longer has her husband by her side.
If he does, he will need to win the support of the middle class, much of which has grown tired of Kirchnerism.
When Argentines return from their summer vacation in March, the wave of sympathy for her will have subsided.
If she wants to win another election, she will have to decide whether or not to repudiate, calmly, many of her husband&#39;s policies.
