An arsenic-resistant microbe raises the possibility of new life forms on Earth... or elsewhere
The discovery of a rare bacterium that can use arsenic as one of its nutrients expands the possibility of finding new forms of life on Earth and possibly on other planets.
Although the researchers discovered the curious bacterium here on Earth, they say it shows that it is possible for life to exist without the major elements they considered essential.
&quot;This organism has a double capacity.&quot;
&quot;It can grow either with phosphorus or with arsenic.&quot;
&quot;That makes it something very peculiar, although it&#39;s close to being a truly &#39;alien&#39; type of life form,&quot; said Paul CW Davies of Arizona State University, a co-author of the report appearing online Thursday in Science publication.
It has long been considered that there are six major elements essential for life: carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulfur.
However, researchers have discovered that the bacterium, found in Mono Lake, California, can continue to grow after replacing phosphorous with arsenic.
&quot;It makes you wonder what else is possible,&quot; said Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University, a co-author of the report.
According to Anbar, the finding is important for the search for life on planets other than Earth, since researchers need to be able to recognize life, to know what it looks like.
The study focuses on a microbe discovered on Earth.
However, the convening of a press conference to discuss it, in which details of the discovery were not disclosed, generated a great deal of speculation on the Internet about the possibility that the report indicated the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
It did not.
What the discovery &quot;does show is that in other planetary settings, there could be organisms that use other elements to power their biochemistry, and that the &#39;standard&#39; set of elements that we think is essential for life may not be as fixed,&quot; said Charles Cockell. , Professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute, Open University, Milton Keynes, UK.
Cockell was not part of the investigation team.
&quot;This work is novel because it demonstrates the substitution of one element for another in biochemistry and basic biochemical structure,&quot; Cockell added.
The discovery was not made by chance.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA&#39;s Institute for Astrobiology, who led the study, focused on Mono Lake because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorous are chemically similar, so he speculated that a microbe exposed to both might substitute one for the other.
&quot;Arsenic is toxic primarily because its chemical behavior is similar to that of phosphorus.&quot;
&quot;Consequently, it can be difficult for organisms to tell them apart.&quot;
&quot;However, arsenic is different enough that it doesn&#39;t work as well as phosphorus, so it gets in and, so to speak, clogs up the biochemical machinery,&quot; Anbar explains.
The researchers collected the bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and exposed it to increasing concentrations of arsenic, which they managed to adapt to and use to grow.
The microbe grows better with phosphorous, but showing that it can live with arsenic instead raises the possibility that arsenic-using life may exist naturally, either elsewhere on Earth or on another planet. or moon where arsenic is most common.
Jamie S. Foster, an assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, noted that the idea that phosphorus can be substituted for arsenic is not new, but an example has never been found to show that it works.
Arsenic was more common in Earth&#39;s earliest ages, he noted, so the researchers speculated that early life forms may have used it.
&quot;It does suggest that there could be other ways of generating life, not just the way life formed on Earth in ancient times,&quot; said Foster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon&#39;s research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Institutes of Health.
