Can civility bridge the divide?
After a campaign notable for invective and negativity, a bit of civility has been unleashed in Washington this week.
Is it a harbinger of genuine bipartisan cooperation to come, or an illusory moment before a quick return to partisan combat in the capital?
Tuesday&#39;s meeting between President Obama and congressional leaders produced no progress on the big issues that must be dealt with during the outgoing session.
But from what everyone is saying, it was at least a polite discussion of the two parties&#39; differences, as well as an acknowledgment of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than just another empty episode to score partisan points.
Wednesday&#39;s public meeting of the president&#39;s deficit commission was equally civil, despite remaining political differences among members.
It seems clear that the close interaction over a period of months generated a mutual respect that transcends the ideological divide that still separates the members.
That&#39;s hardly enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
Now both sides are on a trial run, probing each other for signs of cooperativism and compromise as they try to gauge the limits of public opinion and voter patience for a renewed partisan war.
Which is why the meeting on Tuesday and the subsequent evaluations of it by the participants were made with a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too great and too deep-seated to suggest any rapid climate change that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it&#39;s taxes, spending, healthcare or welfare, the two sides are at opposite poles.
Still, the November election has softened the mood in Washington, at least in the short term.
&quot;There&#39;s no question that things have changed in terms of the way we say things,&quot; said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official now at the Center for Ethics and Public Policy.
&quot;They are inevitable after the elections.
Elections arouse partisan passions, which are then extinguished.
That&#39;s good&quot;.
On some issues, particularly those on the agenda for the outgoing session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush&#39;s tax cuts expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favor of this.
Both sides want to find a way to preserve some or all of the reductions, permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, there is likely to be a compromise to expand unemployment benefits, probably because Republicans can&#39;t make believe they favor tax cuts for the rich by denying unemployment benefits to unemployed workers.
After Tuesday&#39;s meeting at the White House, there is greater optimism for a possible deal on these issues during the outgoing session, along with the ratification of the new START (Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty) nuclear disarmament pact.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution cautions that successful cooperation on the pressing issues of the outgoing session will not necessarily lead to continued bipartisanship when the new 112th. Congress meets in January.
On the contrary, he affirmed that it is very probable and even inevitable that a period of disagreement will begin.
&quot;After the things that must be done are done, in the short term psychology will revert the situation to one of confrontation,&quot; he said.
Wehner, too, expressed skepticism (which is widely shared) that civility can lead to true cooperation.
&quot;I see most of what will happen between now and 2012 as a rehearsal for the main event of 2012,&quot; he said.
The reasons have a lot to do with the constitution of the new Republican House majority and the Tea Party voters who were instrumental in creating it.
As conscious as Republican leaders are of the dangers of exaggerating their position, they know they must try to make good on their promises to cut state spending and repeal the new health care law.
Those party lines are already clear in the initial reactions to the deficit commission&#39;s recommendations, which include reforming the tax code and raising some taxes and the retirement age, and cutting spending.
Co-Chairmen Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have been tasked with one of the toughest jobs in Washington and, by their own estimation, have forced the deficit issue onto the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the 18-member commission to publish their plan as an official recommendation, and they have been struggling to get anywhere near that number.
The greatest resistance is among the elected officials on the panel, suggesting that on fiscal issues there is, at least currently, little basis or desire for compromise.
Galston predicts two phases in the battles between the Republicans in the White House and those in Congress.
The first will come next year in the form of partisan clashes, when Republicans challenge Obama on the budget, taxes and health care, followed later by a period of increased bipartisan cooperation.
What would cause the change?
Public opinion.
There is considerable evidence that, despite the partisanship of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties working together.
If the confrontation leads to deadlock, as it did in 1995, then both parties will carefully watch the reaction of the people.
Whoever they think is losing will likely change course and seek compromise.
However, this may be an optimistic view.
Partisanship and polarization are greater today than they were in the mid-1990s, and there seems to be a bigger ideological gap between Obama and congressional Republicans than there was between President Bill Clinton and Republicans at the time.
At the same time, activists in both parties see 2010 as merely a prelude to a more momentous election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civility on display this week may be welcomed by many Americans.
But this will require much more effort on the part of both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
