Known as &quot;the Butcher&quot; for his brutality during Khmer Rouge rule, the commander remains popular in this remote former Khmer Rouge stronghold in northwest Cambodia, where he built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructure, and where they still live. thousands of former soldiers of the organization.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge surrendered to the government, long-held loyalty is finally being challenged in Anlong Veng.
In April, a local forum for truth and reconciliation allowed victims to publicly confront people who had participated in the regime.
In June, the government distributed a high school textbook here that for the first time teaches the history of the Khmer Rouge to the children of its former soldiers.
And in July, a mixed United Nations-Cambodia court handed down the first conviction of a former Khmer Rouge member, sentencing the former head of the notorious Tuol Sleng torture center, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as Duch, to 35 years. from prison.
With each of those events, anxiety has grown among Anlong Veng&#39;s Khmer Rouge veterans, complicating reconciliation efforts and their attempts to reintegrate into Cambodian society.
&quot;There is resentment and fear among the former Khmer Rouge, but they can&#39;t do anything,&quot; said Chhang Youk, director of the Cambodia Documentation Center, an independent organization that investigates the regime.
&quot;For them, life under the Khmer Rouge was glorious, but the regime has become a symbol of evil.&quot;
&quot;This is creating divisions within families.&quot;
During the Khmer Rouge rule of Cambodia, between 1975 and 1979, approximately 1.7 million people were executed or died of starvation, disease, or overwork.
When the Vietnamese invaded and overthrew the government led by Pol Pot in 1979, the remnants of the regime and its military fled to the Cambodian border with Thailand.
There they launched an insurrection that lasted until the last movement that surrendered in December 1998.
As Pol Pot, Nuon Chea, and Ieng Sary led guerrilla warfare from their bases in the mountains and jungles of western Cambodia, Ta Mok cultivated a following in Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, after a UN-sponsored peace deal led to the country&#39;s first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Khmer Rouge fighters began defecting to the government, culminating in the surrenders of Ieng Sary in 1996, and Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998, and Ta Mok, who had held out, was captured by government forces in 1999 in the nearby Dangrek Mountains.
He died in a Phnom Penh prison in 2006 while awaiting trial.
Without the support of their benefactors, the oldest Khmer Rouge fighters fell into the abject poverty that is common in rural Cambodia, and many are nostalgic for the movement.
Although a few elite Khmer Rouge officials retained their local administrative posts in exchange for laying down their arms, the rank and file soldiers remain poor, unskilled farmers.
&quot;These people have gotten little benefit after the surrender,&quot; said Sok Leang of the Center for Justice and Reconciliation, which holds public forums throughout Cambodia, including in Anlong Veng.
&quot;They have incorporated the utopian agrarian ideology of the regime.&quot;
&quot;They were raised with no concept of doing business.&quot;
Sister Lim, 55, who joined the Khmer Rouge as a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle near Anlong Veng before dedicating herself to life as a poor rice farmer in 1998.
&quot;Life with the Khmer Rouge was fine,&quot; he said.
&quot;Ta Mok fed everyone.&quot;
&quot;But now life is difficult because we have to provide for ourselves.&quot;
The current Khmer Rouge court has also caused concerns here.
Early next year, the court is expected to start prosecuting Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, Ieng Thirith, another former Khmer Rouge minister.
The court&#39;s mandate is to prosecute top leaders and those most responsible for the crimes, but it has not said whether it will pursue cases beyond those four.
This did not do much to assuage Anlong Veng&#39;s fears.
Recent media speculation has focused on Im Chaem, 64, who was a district chief in Banteay Meanchey province during Khmer Rouge rule in the late 1970s.
In 2007, she told investigators from the Cambodia Documentation Center that she had overseen the construction of the Trapeang Thma dam, a project in which thousands of forced laborers are thought to have died.
On a recent muggy afternoon, Im Chaem returned from working in the fields to his house on wooden stilts on a dirt road on the outskirts of Anlong Veng.
As the sun cast long shadows across the parched grass, Im Chaem refused to speak of his Khmer Rouge past.
She stated that if the court summoned her, she would not appear.
&quot;Cambodia is peaceful and stable,&quot; he said.
&quot;If there are more prosecutions, there will be war.&quot;
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who defected from the Khmer Rouge in 1978, has also repeatedly warned of instability if the court goes after more suspects, though this is disputed by experts and historians.
&quot;Cambodia must dig a hole and bury the past,&quot; he said.
But facing the past is just what Cambodia needs to do to move forward, said Chhang Youk of the documentation center.
&quot;Reconciliation, according to Khmer, is putting the broken pieces back together,&quot; he said.
&quot;It is our obligation to put these broken pieces together so that we can understand.&quot;
The center produced the first government-approved textbook on the Khmer Rouge, called the 75-page &quot;A History of Democratic Kampuchea.&quot;
It was distributed in Anlong Veng in June as a supplement to the Ministry of Education&#39;s secondary school history textbook, which contains less than four pages on the Khmer Rouge.
As in most of Cambodia, the young people of Anlong Veng know few details about the Khmer Rouge, despite the town&#39;s link to the regime.
Touch Valeak, 19, a student at Anlong Veng Secondary School, said the new textbook helped students understand an important part of their history.
But her parents were skeptical when she brought the book home to study.
&quot;My family rejects many parts of the textbook and the court,&quot; he said.
&quot;They are suspicious because they are not sure how many people the court will prosecute.&quot;
Such resistance has made the reconciliation process complex and difficult, Sok Leang said.
But the public forums, the textbook and the court are beginning to have an impact, he said.
In any case, here the Khmer Rouge retain a powerful charm.
In the Dangrek Mountains, a path overgrown with weeds and littered with discarded plastic bags leads to a soot-black rectangle covered by a rusty tin roof.
Pol Pot&#39;s body was burned here on a pile of tires after his death in 1998.
Nuom Sothea, 31, a roadside cell phone vendor, said he didn&#39;t know much about the man who was cremated there.
&quot;But he has a strong spirit and many locals go there to pray to him,&quot; he said.
It was Nuom Sothea&#39;s birthday, and later that day she decided to walk to Pol Pot&#39;s last resting place, where she would leave a bunch of ripe bananas in the hope of good luck.
Belarus agrees to give up its stockpile of weapons-grade uranium
In a surprise victory for President Obama&#39;s campaign to protect nuclear material around the world, the Belarusian government announced Wednesday that it will give up its stockpile of highly enriched uranium, a critical component of nuclear weapons.
The deal was revealed in a joint statement released after Foreign Minister Hillary Rodham Clinton met with Belarusian Foreign Minister Sergei Martynov on the sidelines of a security summit.
For years, the US government had been trying to persuade Belarus to give up its highly enriched uranium, and it seemed they had reached a point of no return last spring.
But US officials told the Washington Post that a pair of classified operations were carried out with Belarus in the past two months, to remove 84.82kg of weapons-grade uranium from a Belarusian research facility.
This set the stage for Wednesday&#39;s agreement to remove the rest of the material, roughly 227kg, according to an official, who spoke on condition of anonymity due to the confidentiality of the matter.
The agreement appeared to be one of the most important outcomes of the 47-nation Nuclear Security Summit chaired by Obama in April, which excluded Belarus.
And apparently it was a good achievement to secure the invitation of the former Soviet republic to the next summit in 2012.
&quot;I was really fascinated by the fact that they wanted a seat at the 2012 Nuclear Security Summit.&quot;
&quot;This shows that this process is working,&quot; said Ken Luongo, president of the Society for Global Security, a group that promotes nuclear security.
Clinton called the agreement &quot;a very significant and important step&quot; taken by Belarus.
In April 2009 Obama promised in Prague to protect all vulnerable nuclear material around the world in the next four years.
Since then, the US government has helped six countries get rid of all their highly enriched uranium.
Belarus would be the seventh.
A dozen countries did so under the George W. Bush administration.
At the time of Obama&#39;s Nuclear Security Summit, Belarusian President Alexander Lukashenko had declared that the nation would never give up its uranium.
&quot;We have kept highly enriched uranium (hundreds of kilograms of what is basically weapons-grade uranium) and low-enriched uranium,&quot; Lukashenko said at the time.
&quot;This is our raw material...we are not going to make dirty bombs, and we are not going to sell them to anyone.&quot;
&quot;We use it for research purposes, that&#39;s all.&quot;
However, Belarus reached out to the United States a few months ago, indicating interest in reaching an agreement.
Officials said the first task of removing the uranium from Belarus, in October, was particularly challenging as the material had been lightly irradiated.
Officials said it was loaded onto a special train that traveled more than 2,000 km to a Russian facility for storage and disposal.
According to the officials, the second operation ended on Monday and was carried out by plane.
The US government spent $13 million for the tasks, with most of the money used to supply Belarus with the low-enriched uranium research facility, which is unsuitable for nuclear weapons.
Andrew Bieniawski, an Energy Department official who works on Global Threat Reduction, said &quot;this was very carefully coordinated and orchestrated to build trust&quot; that led to the deal Clinton signed.
The James Martin Center for Nonproliferation Studies estimated this year that Belarus possessed at least 40 kilograms of weapons-grade uranium, as well as hundreds of kilograms of highly enriched uranium.
Belarus will try to remove its reservation by 2012, according to the joint statement.
Relations between Belarus and the United States have been strained for years, mainly due to Lukashenko&#39;s harsh repression of human rights.
But Wednesday&#39;s statement suggested a potential détente.
It stated that &quot;while progress on these global security issues is welcomed, the United States and Belarus recognized that greater respect for democracy and human rights in Belarus remains central to improving bilateral relations, and it is essential for the progress of the country and its citizens&quot;.
