David Álvarez, founder of the group, will challenge, considering it &quot;null and void&quot;, the judicial meeting of El Enebro on the next 16th, requested by five of his seven children and in which they will try to assert their majority and seize the management bodies of the firm that owns Bodegas Vega Sicilia.
David Álvarez and his children Jesús David and María José are fine-tuning the legal battery for the new judicial chapter in their dispute over control of part of the group.
The founder of the largest holding company for business services does not seem willing to give up in his dispute to be present in the governing bodies of El Enebro.
He was removed from his board of directors by five of his seven children who were appointed administrators at the shareholders&#39; meeting on January 18 of this year and whose challenge is recorded in the Mercantile Registry.
The judicial meeting of El Enebro for the next day 16, convened by the Commercial Magistrate Number 2 of Madrid, has once again opened the box of thunder within the Álvarez family.
The appeal to the judge to set the meeting is, until the conflict is resolved, the only legal mechanism that guarantees the convening of the meeting.
The last movement of Juan Carlos, Pablo, Emilio, Marta and Elvira Álvarez Mezquiriz, is described by David Álvarez as a &quot;desperate resource of the applicants, their five children, to, through procedural trickery, in clear fraud of the Law and abuse of rights, treat to validate and clean up the radically null meeting of January 18&quot;, according to their official spokespersons.
This argument will be the basis for, once the meeting is held, to proceed to challenge it, considering that it is &quot;null and void&quot;.
The same protagonists, who maintain a discreet silence, have already unsuccessfully tried to get the magistrate to convene a meeting in June.
In El Enebro, a holding company and owner of Bodegas Vega Sicilia, among other assets, the seven sons of David Álvarez control 100% of the capital.
The founder of the services group claims, however, the usufruct of 51% of the capital, according to family protocols.
This issue is the substantive issue that the judge must decide once the hearing on the challenge claim is held, for which there is still no set date.
Red Bull triumphs in F1 with a secret weapon from Siemens
A software designs improvements in the cars in real time.
Since Red Bull burst into the world of Formula 1 in 2004, its history in this select universe of speed has been marked by surprise and success.
At first no one took into consideration the options of a newly arrived team and, despite the upward trajectory of recent seasons, last November, in the final stretch of the championship, everyone bet on the triumph of Fernando Alonso&#39;s Ferrari.
Without detracting from the skill as a driver of the final champion, the German Sebastian Vettel, nor from the capacity of the Renault engine that powers his car, in the world of Formula 1 the &quot;secret weapon&quot; that the multinational Siemens has become a legend. has put in the hands of Red Bull to make it a winning team.
It is actually a powerful process simulation software that the German put on the market in 2007 for purposes far removed from high-end automotive competition.
Called PLM, this powerful computing tool has been used to design assembly lines for manufacturing factories around the world, power plants, high-precision instruments.
The objective is to faithfully reproduce and simulate the product or process before building it in real life, thus avoiding failures and avoidable expenses.
PLM has facilitated the development of Canon cameras, Sukhoi aircraft or Nissan&#39;s most famous utility cars.
Siegfried Russwurm, head of the industrial division of Siemens, explains that the use of this computer tool in its Formula 1 factory has allowed Red Bull to design and carry out &quot;in a few hours, almost in real time&quot;, the modifications, changes and improvements that are detected during the races and in the tests.
Russwurm explains that the teams in 1992 had an average of 10 technicians on their team who were capable of introducing a maximum of three or four improvements to the vehicles during each season.
Today, 180 highly qualified young professionals work in the Red Bull team who, equipped with powerful computer equipment, analyze and project all sorts of modifications to the cars.
The Siemens manager explained that the PLM software is capable of analyzing and improving all the elements of Red Bull cars with the exception of the engine, which is the sole responsibility of Renault.
Materials, fuel, aerodynamics and safety elements are modified.
Changes can be brought from the virtual reality of the simulator to reality in less than 24 hours, thanks to advanced laser production systems and high-tech autoclaves.
The only limitation of this madness of technological improvement is the figure of 40 million dollars that each Formula 1 team can spend at most each season to facilitate the competition.
Red Bull has set up the high-tech factory to design and produce its racing cars in a town about 50 kilometers from London.
These are two buildings in which visits are restricted, especially for journalists.
Everything that happens there is considered &quot;top secret&quot;.
The staff for this task amounts to 580 people, including its two pilots, the champion Vettel and Mark Webber.
Red Bull&#39;s Formula 1 hero is undoubtedly recent champion Sebastian Vetell.
Among the immense technological resources that the energy drink brand has put at the service of its participation in the circuits, other protagonists hide whose help is invaluable and whose notoriety is null.
The factory&#39;s head of technology, Steve Nevey, says that five years ago it could be said that R&amp;D advances in cart cars contributed 50% of victories and the drivers were responsible for the rest.
Today these percentages have varied and technology accounts for 85% of the success, while the pilots contribute 15% of the added value.
Nevey acknowledges that the Vettel or Webber will never be replaced by computing since &quot;they are unpredictable gladiators.&quot;
HP will install 20 own stores with local distributors in two years
Hewlett-Packard (HP) opened yesterday in Barcelona its first exclusive store in collaboration with its partner Pont Reyes.
This will be the first of the network of 20 shops between 80 and 100 square meters that the multinational plans to install in Spain over the next two years.
The company will make this initiative compatible with the 16 areas already present in multi-brand centers such as PC City, Carrefour, Saturn and El Corte Inglés.
The vice president of HP Spain, Helena Herrero, gave as an example the remodeled store located on Barcelona&#39;s Gran Vía, owned by Pont Reyes, with whom she has collaborated for 30 years.
The North American group has prepared a plan to locate 200 branded points of sale in Europe in 2013, a strategy that includes the 20 Spanish establishments.
The first to open were Bucharest (Romania) and Belgrade (Serbia) last week, with Barcelona being the third.
Herrero did not want to reveal the following possible openings, although he acknowledged that Madrid could be the next destination.
The director of HP personal systems also assured that the philosophy to install the stores will always be the same, relying on a local distributor with experience and knowledge of the sector.
The North American group advises and is in charge of the exclusive furniture design of the stores (with products that can be touched interactively), which in Europe will have an identical image.
In addition, HP covers the training of store personnel.
Helena Herrero denied that it was a franchise system and stressed that the exclusive network of shops aims to &quot;improve customer service and SMEs in purchasing, customer service, after-sales and even packaging&quot;.
The Barcelona store includes a space with a pioneering pilot program worldwide that is responsible for solving possible problems with HP computer equipment under warranty.
An online service connects with a technical center located in Maastricht (Netherlands).
&quot;Thus, in 10 minutes we can solve problems that can sometimes take up to two days.&quot;
&quot;This system is specially designed for SMEs and users, since large companies already have contracted technical assistance services,&quot; Helena Herrero remarked yesterday.
Sabadell bets on &#39;stealing&#39; a million customers from its rivals in three years
More optimistic than other executives, the CEO of Banco Sabadell, Jaime Guardiola, believes that 2011 will be a tough year for banks, but initially rules out a new liquidity crisis and predicts the end of the liability war.
Despite this, it foresees a collapse in interest margins, which they will try to partially compensate with increases in commissions and the price of credit.
Sabadell expects to capture one million private customers in three years, its pending issue.
Sabadell has found a way to exploit the next three years and thus be able to survive in a very difficult economic environment.
The bank will launch a new master plan in 2011 that will be valid for three years.
The objective, in addition to surviving without the need to resort to public aid from the FROB, is to gain market share by attracting one million new individual customers -700,000 if those who can leave the bank are discounted-, his great pending issue, since until now it had pampered SMEs and companies more than the retail client.
This year it has attracted 250,000 individual customers and 50,000 companies.
Its market share in individuals is 3.5%, while in companies it exceeds 10%.
Another of the bases of the 2011-2013 plan is the commitment to productivity, or what is the same, austerity, with cost reduction as an objective, and whose challenges will be exposed by the bank when it presents the results of the year.
Few banks dare these days to set goals and make them public, since the financial crisis has disrupted all the plans of world banks.
Sabadell, in fact, will close its Optima master plan this year, set four years ago, although initially it was for three, but the market situation meant that it will extend it for one more year.
Customers who let savings banks escape will be their main target.
In a breakfast organized by the APIE, Guardiola insisted that 2011 is going to be a &quot;difficult and transcendental&quot; year.
The executive, in fact, believes that the way out of the crisis in Spain &quot;will be slow.&quot;
In addition, in two or three years it will be &quot;very difficult to create jobs&quot;, something essential for the survival of the banking business, he insisted.
And, although he believes that the liability war - which penalizes margins - is falling, the price of the risk premiums that banks and savings banks are paying for their issues to obtain liquidity are already being transferred to the price of credit to compensate for the fall from the margins.
&quot;The issue of liquidity and financing is structural, and it is going to be a factor of pressure on credit.&quot;
&quot;We have not closed the tap, but the differentials are higher,&quot; Guardiola acknowledged.
Banesto already gave orders to its network on Thursday to limit long-term credit and raise the price of spreads -see CincoDías on November 22 and 27-.
He also acknowledged that the banking trend now &quot;is to raise commissions&quot;, but &quot;there is a competitive framework&quot;.
Sabadell&#39;s master plan is based on organic growth, although, as always, the group does not rule out corporate operations.
Not surprisingly, he assures that in Spain &quot;larger sizes will be required.&quot;
&quot;Next year everything is going to move,&quot; he said.
He affirms that the capital needs are &quot;increased a lot&quot; and does not rule out that some Spanish financial entity enters into the red.
And he points out that the FROB can replace the market in raising funds before new recapitalizations.
After assuring that Sabadell can survive the temporary closure of the markets, he downplayed what some bankers are already predicting as a new liquidity crisis.
He points out that it cannot be issued, but contrary to what happened in June, short-term financing can be obtained through repos, which cushions the crisis.
CECA rules out a second wave of mergers in savings banks
The director general of CECA, José Antonio Olavarrieta, ruled out yesterday that there is going to be a wave of mergers of savings banks and once again insisted on the speed with which the restructuring of the sector is being carried out.
When the concentration process of the Spanish savings banks began, there were several entities that assured that they would not participate in this first phase and that they would reserve themselves for the second round.
However, the director general of the Spanish Confederation of Savings Banks (CECA), José Antonio Olavarrieta, ruled out yesterday that this new wave of operations is going to take place.
&quot;I think that most of the mergers have been done, the incorporation of Cajasol into the Banca Cívica group cannot be said to be a second round, what there are are adjustments.&quot;
&quot;Most of it is completely done; instead of 17 we may go to 13 or 14 but all the major processes have already been done and supervised by the Bank of Spain, which has also collaborated a lot in that,&quot; said the manager.
In declarations during a breakfast of the Association of Directors and Executives of Aragon (ADEA), Olavarrieta has explained that the concentration process is being undertaken &quot;at the highest possible speed, and we have to be very satisfied with how it is taking place within the deadlines that in their day, not now, were marked in the business plans with the Bank of Spain&quot;, he emphasized.
&quot;Going from 45 savings banks with an average of 28,500 million assets to 17 with 75,500 million is a process that has no parallel in history, reducing the number of entities by 62% so that they are much larger to comply with Basel &quot;, he highlighted.
Olavarrieta acknowledged that &quot;there are a series of rather unfortunate opinions about the slowness of the process&quot; that demonstrate &quot;a lack of seriousness and sense&quot;, because &quot;what the Bank of Spain does is remember that we have to be within the deadline before end of the year&quot;.
The general director of CECA, José Antonio Olavarrieta, assured yesterday that Spain has the most rigorous financial system in all of Europe and &quot;probably&quot; in the world, and attributed to those who question it a &quot;lack of knowledge&quot;.
The manager pointed out that, within the current economic situation, &quot;we can be very calm&quot; with the situation of financial institutions and savings banks, a system that has undertaken a &quot;very important&quot; concentration process and that &quot;is going to fastest possible speed.
He also recalled that Spanish banks did very well in the stress tests carried out by the ECB in July.
Shoemaker and the German Red Line
Berlin has chosen to remain in the euro, but has set the conditions for the entire Union.
The tensions in the markets have provoked a double governmental response.
On the one hand, José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero has advanced new adjustment measures, from tax reductions for SMEs, regulation of private employment agencies or suppression of the 426 euros of aid for the unemployed without benefit, to the privatization of 49% of AENA, of the management of the Barajas and El Prat airports and of 30% of State Lotteries.
On the other, Vice President Elena Salgado, with the support of former President Felipe González, has joined the criticism of Chancellor Angela Merkel for her responsibility in unleashing the current crisis.
How should these movements be interpreted?
Go ahead, Merkel&#39;s position is not an error in her communication policy.
On the contrary, it is another twist in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
And there Germany has a radically new vision of what its future should be, which clashes with maintaining the old traditions of a large part of its partners.
Faced with European resistance, speculation in Germany begins about the three possible solutions to the crisis.
The first, a strong euro, made up of itself, Austria and the Netherlands, among other countries, while the south would leave the monetary zone.
The second, the recovery of the framework, although now it seems like science fiction, with a current of very favorable opinion, close to 50% of the population.
The third, a redesign of the euro, in line with the German proposals for greater macroeconomic control, budgetary rigor, fines for transgressing countries, possible suspension of payments by some of them and extension to the private sector of the costs of potential adjustments.
The German position is clear and has been defined for a long time, so now there are no excuses.
First, in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission stimulated deficits, the German government came up with a constitutional reform to prevent them from 2016.
This was the first sign of divergence between what Germany believed should be done (fiscal rigor plans and stability in public finances), and what its European partners, including France, were practicing.
The second on the forehead was given by the Central European country when Merkel painfully dragged out the decision to rescue Greece.
Even then it was the subject of fierce criticism, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and public and published opinion were very much against the bailout of Greece.
Finally, in the last days of October, Merkel again emerges with a clear position, demanding the reform of the treaties of the Union, to make it possible to rescue a country and, at the same time, force private lenders to run with part of the cost.
This position has been interpreted as anti-European, since it has precipitated the Irish crisis and everything else.
But his proposal, although somewhat sweetened, has been approved and, in the coming months, we should attend the reform process of the Union that will make those measures possible as of 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not intend to cross.
And he is telling us all that, although measures must now be taken with which he perhaps does not quite agree, from that date the old functioning of the euro will have ended.
2013 will mean the birth of a new currency area, in which offending countries will be severely penalized, may be forced to declare bankruptcy and, in this case, the private sector will also bear part of the cost.
Germany is telling us that we must follow a severe path of growth with high savings and investment rates, moderation in consumption, improvements in productivity and competitiveness, and positive external balances.
Another alternative based on debt and construction, with huge holes in the balance of payments, like the one that has presided over Spanish growth in the boom years, they simply will not tolerate.
The challenge is clear.
And we would do wrong not to understand it.
It is not just about bringing the public deficit back to 3% in 2013.
What they demand of us is much harder.
And the worst thing we could do in these circumstances is fool ourselves.
I hope that the current turmoil will give way to greater calm.
And that we take advantage of the window of opportunity that we have been given, until the spring of 2013.
It seems that President Zapatero has also understood it this way and his double manifesto (the reforms promised after last Saturday&#39;s meeting with the big companies and yesterday&#39;s announcement of new measures) suggests that, despite the criticism of Merkel, he has opened up I walk the thesis that you have to put order at home.
But the red line that Germany has drawn is there, and it does not seem that they are going to move it.
And, among the possibilities that are contemplated, that of abandoning a currency zone that is too crowded with countries that are not very serious, cannot be excluded.
Then, Germany will always be able to tell us that it had already warned us.
Sport and law fraud
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos against Ajax show ingenuity but not the will to escape a sanction.
The expulsion allegedly engineered by two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the match played on November 23 against Ajax in the Champions League has caused rivers of ink to be written about whether or not such behavior is unsportsmanlike and if, eventually, both players had to be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is well known, with a few minutes to go in the game (which their team had already clearly won), the two players deliberately wasted time drawing free kicks to provoke the referee to show them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since Real Madrid will end up as the leader of their group, both players will serve the regulatory sanction in the next league game, against Auxerre, and will be able to advance to the next phase with no cards.
Finally, the UEFA disciplinary committee has penalized the team&#39;s coach, José Mourinho, with two games and different financial amounts for the players involved.
The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances like this or similar is not a new practice, but rather frequent in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, of the unwritten but followed rules of this sport.
Part of the debate that arose in the reported case is due to the fact that it has been carried out by a team from the entity of Real Madrid (which in its anthem boasts of nobility and honor, and which on past occasions has fined its players for similar acts) and the dramatization orchestrated, apparently, by Mourinho, who adds another episode to his long history as a histrionic and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this type of behavior not expressly prohibited by the regulations contradicts the principles of sport, that is, if these actions commit legal fraud; Well, in effect, they are actions that respect the sports regulations, but they seem to elude their meaning.
The question goes through examining the type of damage they cause to the sportsmanship.
One of the assets that sportsmanship includes is the physical integrity of the opposing players, an aspect that was not endangered by these actions, that is, there was no violent game.
Another of these goods that is alluded to with fair play is to prevent the team of the offending players from taking unfair advantage of the opposing team, which did not happen either.
Now, the paradoxical thing about the action of the Real Madrid players is that it did not conform to what we normally characterize as cheating or legal fraud, since their violation of the rules was not done secretly to try to avoid sanction, but rather that precisely his action tried to be the most obvious in order to receive the punishment of the referee.
They expected and gladly accepted the penalty.
Another issue is what kind of advantage offenders gain in the intentional fouls examined.
Here it seems necessary to verify that the rival is not placed in a disadvantageous situation or benefit is obtained in the same game, since obviously the result of the action means leaving the team with fewer players.
And it is not a useful strategy for the next game either, since the club will not be able to count on those players.
The advantage, obviously, is that the players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future match.
But it is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indeterminacy, since the team can be eliminated at the first change, and also with this action the players serve a one-match ban and go to the second cycle of cards, in in which the suspension due to the accumulation of cards occurs with one less than in the first cycle.
So, going through rounds, it is not so clear that it is an advantage.
In short, these actions do not go against the sporting spirit, which is part of making strategic decisions that favor getting the most out of what the rules allow.
In the case at hand, the players did not act to evade the application of the sanction (this would indeed be a clear case of legal fraud), but rather they chose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without avoiding punishment or running away from it.
Although the line between ingenuity and legal fraud is blurred, on this occasion I think it was a clear case of ingenuity.
The controversy, it seems to me, arises from two factors: because it involved two self-expulsions and the way in which the directive to provoke them was transmitted.
The damage caused to the principles of the sport by these actions is not so much ethical as aesthetic.
Bid offensive to attract group Christmas dinners in BCN
The dictatorship of the calendar concentrates this year an avalanche of reservations for the 16th and 17th.
Self-supported celebrations by employees proliferate, who want to spend between 20 and 30 euros.
Like the nougat and the lottery, with the arrival of December the pre-Christmas group dinners also return, which continue to act as an oxygen balloon for restaurants and leisure in Barcelona, but which, due to the crisis, have led to an offensive of adjusted prices to be able to capture the majority customer: almost all of them want to spend between 20 and 30 euros on dinners or lunches, agree the businessmen and associations of the sector interviewed.
To finish complicating the accounting, this year&#39;s calendar (with New Year&#39;s Eve falling on a Friday) has concentrated requests in the week of December 13, with the result to date of an avalanche of dinner reservations for peak days (the 16 and 17) and hardly movement for the previous week.
As has been happening since 2008, when the lean days began, there are many companies that have eliminated collective dinners for budgetary reasons.
In order not to dispense with the tradition, many workers maintain it by paying out of their own pocket.
Whatever the situation, both demand competitive prices, confirms the president of the Barcelona Restoration Association, Gaietà Farràs.
The employer&#39;s representative, to this day, does not dare to predict what the festivities will be like this month.
&quot;People think long before booking.&quot;
&quot;He wants to go out but he has the alerts on the issue of prices,&quot; he says.
The business will go well &quot;to those who provide quality at a good price and with good service,&quot; he adds, and recalls that customers tend to go down one step with the crisis, so that the range around 25 euros has become majority in demand.
In a survey in various downtown establishments, the collapse of requests for the night of the 17th is confirmed.
In the Soteras group, they indicate that there is a real boom in requests for that Friday, with the intention of spending less than 30 euros, to which they have responded by adapting their menus to the situation, with complete formulas from 25 to 35 euros.
In another of the most powerful groups, Andilana, with 16 establishments in the city (Hostal de la Rita, Market, La Fonda and others), the peculiarity of the calendar has led to more advance booking, even since the beginning of November.
&quot;We have done the impossible to maintain the same prices as last year, with menus for all tastes from 19.95 to 30 euros,&quot; they detail.
At AN Grup, which is led by El Mussol, Attic, QuQu, and up to a total of 23 stores, they remain optimistic after detecting a billing boom since the second semester and good, although concentrated, business prospects for Christmas.
Sources from the group point out that the 18th will also be a hyperactive day for groups of friends who are pre-celebrating the holidays.
They have added a Christmas menu to their six group menus, with 30 euros or more as the star budget and the perception that there is a predisposition to spend 10% more than last year in exchange for demanding more details, such as cava.
They also see green shoots in some companies that invite their employees back and a feeling that the volume of the groups is somewhat higher.
On behalf of the Fecasarm employers&#39; association (which includes entities such as the Association of Bars, Restaurants and Leisure of Barcelona), its vice-president, Enric Gomà, is confident that he is beginning to see the end of the tunnel and maintains that overall reservations are &quot;encouraged&quot;, although clients &quot;bargain to the max&quot;.
Of course, the illusion for the festivities has not decreased, whoever pays pays, he indicates.
The Pakistani nuclear program causes great concern in the US
Islamabad produces atomic weapons &quot;at a faster rate than any other country.&quot;
Wikileaks leaks confirm links between the Taliban and Pakistan.
The content of the correspondence between the US embassy in Pakistan and the US State Department leaked by the Wikileaks portal confirms the enormous concerns that the Pakistani nuclear program causes in Washington.
Apart from the enlightening and juicy details that they offer about the content of the conversations and the thoughts of the American diplomatic representatives accredited in Islamabad, the documents reveal that the cooperation between the two countries in terms of atomic security, instead of increasing, &quot;decreases&quot;, and that the unstable Asian country produces nuclear weapons &quot;at a faster rate than any other country in the world&quot;.
The peculiarity of the Pakistani nuclear program - that the weapons are not assembled but rather are stored by components to make it difficult to destroy them in the event of an attack - constitutes one of the main reasons for Washington&#39;s sleeplessness.
This is how the ambassador to Pakistan, Anne W. Patterson, lists it in a report prior to the visit of the then National Security adviser, James Jones: &quot;The proximity of some nuclear facilities to territory under Taliban attack, the rumored dispersion of nuclear materials and the vulnerability of transporting atomic materials&quot;.
The large number of people involved in nuclear arsenals and missile programs is seen, not only by the US, but also by Russia, as proliferating and a reason to keep our guard up.
&quot;Pakistan has had to hire personnel with strict religious beliefs to protect nuclear facilities; given the drop in educational and cultural levels, extremist organizations have more opportunities to recruit people to work on nuclear or missile programs,&quot; said the expert Yuri Korolev of the Russian Foreign Ministry in a meeting with his American counterparts.
The latest in the documentation leaked through Julian Assange&#39;s website is the diminishing cooperation between the US and Pakistan on nuclear proliferation issues and Pakistan&#39;s high rate of production of nuclear weapons.
Calling communication with Pakistan &quot;frustrating,&quot; an embassy dispatch in May said: &quot;Transparency is often non-existent; offers of help go unanswered or dismissed.&quot;
In another message, Peter Lavoy, National Intelligence official for South Asia, notes that &quot;despite the economic catastrophe, Pakistan produces nuclear weapons at a faster rate than any other country in the world.&quot;
Ambassador Patterson also asks Washington, during a visit by the head of the Army, General Ashfaq Kayani, to make it &quot;very clear&quot; to the person in charge that &quot;the Pakistan Army must end tacit support for terrorist groups.&quot;
On the hunt for the Wikileaks boss
Obama appoints a senior person in charge of the fight against terrorism to prevent new leaks.
Interpol issues a red alert in order to follow the movements and locate Assange where he is.
Everything related to Wikileaks and its founder, Julian Assange, forms a complicated maze where it is difficult to be certain about the facts.
Yesterday Interpol issued a &quot;red alert&quot; to &quot;locate and follow the movements&quot; of Assange.
However, this is not a traditional arrest warrant.
In addition, it is not new, but dates from November 20.
And it has nothing to do with the latest leak of more than a quarter of a million US diplomatic documents but with the sexual abuse allegations the Australian faces in Sweden.
In addition, the lawyer for the creator of Wikileaks, Mark Stephens, assures that &quot;the police know where and how to contact Mr. Assange.&quot;
It was on the 20th when the international police force based in Lyon (France) issued the order at the request of Sweden, but did not reveal it until yesterday, after receiving authorization from the authorities of that country.
Thus, the 188 countries of Interpol have instructions to identify or locate Assange &quot;with a view to his provisional arrest and extradition.&quot;
Although Interpol cannot order the arrest of an individual affected by a red alert, many of the member countries, as explained by the organization, do consider the so-called red notice a free way to proceed with an arrest -- which must be carried out by the national body police - especially if they have a bilateral extradition agreement, as is the case in Sweden and England, where Assange is believed to be.
The movement has outraged Assange&#39;s lawyers, who yesterday published a letter denouncing that the 39-year-old founder of Wikileaks has shown himself willing to answer questions from the Swedish authorities by videoconference.
They also recall that Assange requested and obtained permission to leave Sweden from the prosecutor in his case, whom they compare to the mythical Lavrentiy Pavlovich Beria, Stalin&#39;s security chief.
&quot;This looks like a hunt, not a legal pursuit,&quot; denounces the letter.
While the world is looking for him - and from Australia his mother defends her son&#39;s innocence - Assange remains unaccounted for, but not silent.
On Monday, he gave an interview to the director of Time magazine via Skype from an undetermined location, a conversation in which he called for the resignation of the US Secretary of State, Hillary Clinton.
&quot;If it can be shown that he was responsible for ordering US diplomats to spy on the UN in violation of international treaties the US has signed, he should resign,&quot; he said.
His opinion was reviled yesterday by the White House press secretary, Robert Gibbs, who described the resignation request as &quot;ridiculous and absurd&quot;.
&quot;I&#39;m not entirely sure why we should care about the opinion of a guy with a website,&quot; he told CNN.
Obama himself has commissioned a senior person in charge of the fight against terrorism, Russell Travers, to prevent new document leaks.
President Barack Obama&#39;s spokesman&#39;s attempt to downplay Assange stands in stark contrast to views being hawked these days by conservative politicians and commentators.
Peter King, the congressman who from January will chair the Homeland Security Committee in the lower house, has asked the State Department to study the possibility of including Wikileaks in the list of terrorist organizations &quot;to intervene and their funds and persecute anyone who gives them any contribution or help&quot;.
Further still has gone Tom Flanagan, an adviser to Canadian President Stephen Harper, who has had to retract after saying Assange should &quot;be assassinated.&quot;
&quot;Obama should target it and use a drone or something.&quot;
The one who did not apologize was Mike Huckabee, a Baptist minister, former governor of Arkansas and possible presidential candidate.
&quot;Whoever in government leaked the information is guilty of treason and anything short of execution would be too kind a punishment,&quot; he told Fox.
Puigcercós seeks peace in ERC with nods to those related to Carod
The Republican leader will allow the party a secret vote on its continuity.
Huguet proposes a more plural executive and the end of the assembly system.
Joan Puigcercós seems to have found the recipe to overcome the umpteenth internal revolt in the ranks of the ERC, without direction due to the loss of 11 deputies and half of the votes.
