The Senate version of the Dream Act or American Dream law would legalize some 800,000 young people who entered the United States before the age of 16, have remained in the country for the last five years, and entered an institution of higher education or the military.
But supporters need 60 votes to pass the initiative, which requires a handful of Republicans to compete, at a time when organizations supporting the project are lobbying intensely to guarantee the law&#39;s approval.
Democrats, a majority of whom support the Dream Act, have 58 seats.
Yet at least one of them, Sen. Ben Nelson of Nebraska, has said he will vote against it, and only one Republican has expressed support for the bill, Richard Lugar of Indiana.
For this reason, supporters of the Dream Act need to add several Republicans in case other Democrats decide to turn their backs on the initiative.
Among the most courted Republicans are Maine Sens. Olympia Snowe and Susan Collins, as well as outgoing Sen. George Lemieux of Florida, who completed the term of Sen. Mel Martinez.
Other Republicans who have supported the Dream Act in the past include Orrin Hatch of Utah and Kay Bailey Hutchinson of Texas, but have said they will not support it another time.
Another Republican he supported, John McCain, has not defined his position at this time.
Although the House of Representatives has a different version, analysts agree that the Dream Act faces the biggest obstacles in the Senate.
