Yesterday, in Cancun, the UN proposed a plan to renew domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in one hundred countries to reduce greenhouse gases (GHG) in an amount that corresponds to practically one third of the additional reduction that must be carried out carried out to stabilize the planet&#39;s climate before 2020.
This ambitious plan is part of the set of large concrete projects that the UN expects to be adopted in Cancun to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments in industrialized countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if incandescent bulbs, which still monopolize between 50 and 70% of the market, are replaced by compact fluorescent bulbs or, even better, by light-emitting diode bulbs (DEL or &quot;LED&quot; in English), it would prevent much of the 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of GHGs emitted on the planet to light humans.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
It is the equivalent to 70% of the emissions of the planetary car park.
In Copenhagen last year, large emitting countries such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans that were to reduce global GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, 5 Gt of said amount should still be reduced to stabilize, before 2020, the increase in temperatures by two degrees Celsius to prevent it from getting out of control.
In incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy is dissipated as heat and the rest, that is, 5%, produces light.
In the case of fluo-compact bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by 75% and with the new LED bulbs, energy consumption is reduced two times more.
Fluo-compact bulbs last an average of between 6,000 and 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, such as those launched by the manufacturer Philips this week (a company that has also participated in the UN study), have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a incandescent bulb, which allows us to get an idea of the savings that can be achieved with the replacement plan that would be applied in a hundred countries.
These new bulbs can also be powered by dimmers and emit very little heat.
Above, they do not contain any mercury.
Various specialists have expressed their reservations regarding compact fluo bulbs, since they contain mercury and must be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless the manufacturers post instructions.
However, the report indicates, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet are not compact fluorescent light bulbs, but coal-fired power plants, which emit a large amount of mercury to produce electricity that is wasted with incandescent light bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury per year.
The report details the advantages that this international program would offer to each country.
For example, Indonesia would thus save one billion dollars a year in electricity and eight million tons of CO2, that is, the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power plants whose construction would cost 2,500 million.
