Snow and ice: 24 departments in orange alert
Snowfall continues to cause traffic difficulties, especially on the secondary network in Brittany, and may affect various economic activities.
Currently, twenty-four departments are on orange alert due to the risk of snowfall and ice formation.
Eure, Eure-et-Loir, Deux-Sèvres and Vienne have joined the twenty departments that were already on orange alert, eighteen from Wednesday at noon and two, the Dordogne and Gironde, joined the group at night.
According to Météo France, the heavy snowfall affects the north of the Gironde and Charentes, although it also snows lightly in the Île-de-France.
Snow layers of between 2 and 5 cm are expected, occasionally between 7 and 10 cm, in the affected departments, and between 1 and 3 cm, or even up to 5 cm, in the Parisian region.
The affected departments are Charente, Charente-Maritime, Côtes d&#39;Armor, Finistère, Gironde, Dordogne, Poitou and those of the Lower Normandy, Île-de-France and Limousin regions.
The snowfalls are strong enough to cause traffic difficulties and affect some economic activities, warns Météo France.
In the Côtes d&#39;Armor, access to several departmental roads has been prohibited for heavy vehicles over 7.5 tons, including the Guingamp-Lannion and Saint-Brieuc-Loudéac axes.
According to the gendarmes, driving on the Brittany secondary network is complicated, which is why they recommend that you not drive except in case of need and certain TER vehicles have been prohibited from driving during the day.
During Thursday, school transport has been prohibited in Picardy.
No specific measure had been planned on Wednesday night to limit the circulation of heavy vehicles.
The prefecture &quot;urges all drivers to drive with the utmost care on the roads and to adapt their driving to the situation.&quot;
The General Directorate of civil aviation (DGAC) asked airlines to cancel 25% of their flights at the Parisian airport of Roissy and 10% at Orly on Thursday due to the expected snowfall.
The DGAC recommends that air passengers contact their airline.
In Great Britain, Gatwick airport, south of London, and Edinburgh airport, in Scotland, are closed until Thursday morning.
Metro of the Grand Paris: first financial drafts
Since the debate on the modernization of transport in the Île-de-France has reached its peak, it rains billions.
At least in the debate.
In particular, we are talking about the 23,000 million for the Grand Paris metro to be built by the Société du Grand Paris.
To initiate this SGP, the State has announced an allocation of funds of 4,000 million euros.
On a theoretical level, this amount will be what will later allow the SGP to obtain loans in the markets to finance part of its double loop.
Today, finally, we have the first accounts.
The amending finance law of 2010, examined in the finance commission of the National Assembly this morning, contains the provisions for finding the first part of that money.
There are two ways: the creation of a special tax on equipment and the increase in the tax on offices in the Ile-de-France.
The first, as we read in article 15 of the text of the bill, is &quot;for the benefit of the public institution Société du Grand Paris.&quot;
In addition, it is fixed in numbers: &quot;The product of this tax is 117 million euros a year.&quot;
The second is a modification of a tax on offices that already exists &quot;to modernize it, increase its product and allocate said increase to the Société du Grand Paris.&quot;
How much would be obtained with this method?
Who knows.
No figures are given in the text.
But it is far from 4,000 million.
&quot;It is specified that the fiscal resources are added to the 4,000 million euros of the allocation of funds that the State will mobilize and that will be granted to the Société du Grand Paris as the project progresses,&quot; we can read in the explanatory statement.
The SGP is not surprised by this system.
&quot;From the moment revenue is created (the two taxes, ndlr), we can cover the studies for three years and then receive the 4,000 million later, as we explained.&quot;
&quot;It will be recorded in the budget and used on an as-needed basis.&quot;
The SGP calculates that it will begin to receive the 4,000 million in 2013 for the 2014 budget.
This device, in which the promised 4,000 million do not appear in the credit, can cause a slightly heated parliamentary debate.
