Avenging hackers and diligent spies
The WikiLeaks affair has a double value.
On the one hand, it reveals an apparent scandal, a scandal that only seems like a scandal in the face of the hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes on an international scale and foresees a future dominated by regression.
But let&#39;s go step by step.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation of the fact that every file created by a secret service (regardless of the nation to which it belongs) consists exclusively of press clippings.
The &quot;extraordinary&quot; US revelations about Berlusconi&#39;s sexual mores merely reflect what has been written for months in any newspaper (except those belonging to Berlusconi) and the sinisterly ridiculing profile of Gaddafi has long given ideas to artists of cabaret to create their skits.
The rule that secret files should only consist of news that is public knowledge is essential to the dynamics of the secret services, and not only in this century.
If you visit a bookstore dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each work repeats (about the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rosicrucians) exactly what had been written in the previous works.
This is not only because the authors of occult texts do not want to do new research (or do not know where to look for news about the non-existent), but because those who dedicate themselves to occultism do not only trust what they already know, which reconfirms what that they had already learned.
This is the mechanism of Dan Brown&#39;s success.
The same applies to secret files.
The informant is lazy, just as the head of the secret services is lazy (or has little eagerness) (otherwise it could be, I don&#39;t know, editor of Libération), who only considers true what he can recognize.
The top secret information about Berlusconi that the US embassy in Rome sent to the State Department was the same as that published in Newsweek the week before.
So why have the disclosures of these files caused such a stir?
On the one hand, they are just saying what every educated person already knows, namely that embassies, at least since World War II and since Heads of State can call each other on the phone or fly to dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of some limited exercises of representation, have become centers of espionage.
Any viewer who watches investigative films knows this perfectly well, we just pretend that we don&#39;t know out of hypocrisy.
In any case, the fact of repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy and gives a bad image of US diplomacy.
Second, the idea that any hacker could see the top secrets of the most powerful country in the world greatly affects the prestige of the State Department.
Therefore, the scandal affects both the victims and the &quot;executioners&quot;.
But let&#39;s get into the true nature of what has happened.
In the past, in Orwell&#39;s time, all power could be conceived as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell&#39;s prophecy has come true since, being able to control every move thanks to the telephone, every transaction made, hotel visited, highway taken, the citizen thus became a complete victim of the eye of power.
But when it is shown, as it is now, that even the crypts of power&#39;s secrets cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control relationship ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen (at least the hacker, chosen as the citizens&#39; avenger) can know all the secrets of power.
How can you put up with a power that can no longer even keep its own secrets?
It is true, as Georg Simmel already said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); It is also true that all knowledge about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is actually an empty secret, without a secret, since it comes from the public sphere; but revealing, as WikiLeaks has done, that Hillary Clinton&#39;s secrets were empty secrets is taking away all power.
WikiLeaks hasn&#39;t done any harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but it did, and a lot, to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound caused to such a powerful power?
It is clear that, in the future, States will no longer be able to put any confidential information on the Internet, since it would be like publishing it on a billboard in the middle of the street.
But it is also clear that, with today&#39;s technologies, you cannot expect to have confidential conversations over the phone.
Nothing is easier than finding out if and when a Head of State has flown in and made contact with one of the counterparts.
How will they be able to maintain private and confidential relationships in the future?
I know perfectly well that, for the moment, my forecast is something out of science fiction and, therefore, fictional, but I imagine government agents who move discreetly in stagecoaches with uncontrollable itineraries, carrying messages that have been memorized or, at most, hiding some data written on the heels of his shoes.
That information is then kept, in a single copy, in locked drawers: after all, the Watergate spy attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
In the past, I have written that technology currently crabs, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet has once again created a wired (telephone) telegraph.
Videotapes (analogue) had allowed film researchers to study a film step by step, going forward and backward, discovering all the secrets of editing, whereas now CDs (digital) only allow you to go forward or backward from chapter to chapter. , that is, to enormous proportions.
With high-speed trains, we can go from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, with the travel involved, we need three and a half hours.
Therefore, it is nothing out of the ordinary that politics and communication techniques lead us back to horse-drawn carriages.
One last comment.
In the past, the press tried to understand what was secretly going on in the embassies.
At present, it is the embassies that request confidential information from the press.
Climate: the bungling of France in its financing promises
One year after the Copenhagen Accord, it is time to examine whether the rapidly unlocked financing promises (called fast start or early) made by developed countries have been respected.
And the French bungling has been revealed.
In the Copenhagen Accord, developed countries pledged to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union promised to contribute 7,200 million euros in three years and France 1,260 million euros (that is, 420 million a year).
During the opening of COP16, the EU has put its best cards on the table to convince its partners that its commitment to fast start financing is true: a report detailing the measures of its Member States, a press conference, a big side event, flyer distribution...
Operation Transparency turned out to be appreciable and was appreciated for what it really is worth: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same and with the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released 2,200 million euros in 2010, which places it on the right track towards fulfilling its commitment of 7,200 million in 2012.
But, if we study the situation in detail, things are more complicated.
Under the Copenhagen Accord, the money must be &quot;new and additional&quot; to ensure that a complementary effort is made, without hurting official development assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no agreement on what &quot;new and additional&quot; means.
When the European Commission proposed harmonization, some Member States, including France, have blocked the procedure.
Currently, everyone chooses the reference that best suits them.
For example, the European Commission has taken 2009 as a reference: international financing is maintained and 150 million are added over three years as fast start financing.
Other countries have chosen similar benchmarks in terms of the year or level of official development assistance.
On the contrary, France considers the financing of &quot;all new projects&quot; for the year 2010 to be &quot;new and additional&quot;.
In other words, no reference is made to spending in previous years or to the total level of official development assistance.
In particular, the total amount of France&#39;s aid to developing countries may remain stable (or even decrease), while it claims to honor its commitment on &quot;new and additional&quot; funds...
Another crucial element, the distribution between donations and loans.
Once again, there is no standard and everyone chooses the method of calculation.
Some, like France, consider that every euro lent is equivalent to a euro donated.
Obviously, such a thing is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
Although the use of loans may be justified for certain investments that are profitable (frequently projects related to emission reductions that are based on more efficient technologies), it is fallacious to present a euro that will be recovered as equivalent to a euro that will be donate... At most, only the cost of borrowing for the lending country (ie the equivalent of one interest rate) should count towards your commitments.
But France does not find such reasoning useful: it &quot;respects&quot; its commitment of 420 million euros by making 91.5% loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% donations (36.1 million euros). ; check out the EU document to see for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union that uses the loan so frequently.
Germany uses it by 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia, among others, respect their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the majority of the European Union contributes one euro to fulfill its commitment, France only contributes ten cents and considers that the effort is comparable.
A nice trick!
In short, in its fast start financing, France is committing a double abuse: on the one hand, in relation to actions over time and, on the other, in relation to the actual financial effort.
By spending just €36.1 million, he manages to give the impression that he is spending a &quot;new and additional&quot; €420 million, as promised.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that it is Bercy who has dealt with the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other Member States continue to donate when they can simply lend?) and in negotiations, since developing countries are not fools...
The chapter on early financing is a trifle, relatively short-term, in relation to the climate negotiations as a whole.
But it could be one too many grains of sand in the immense machinery that is the UNFCCC.
Let&#39;s hope that&#39;s not the case.
Be that as it may, it is essential to learn from this first year of early financing.
Firstly, France could announce a change in its calculation method for the years 2011 and 2012, with the intention of respecting its commitments and in the same way as the other countries of the European Union.
But, especially, France could move forward the discussions on in-play betting in relation to long-term financing (another essential chapter currently being discussed): we will not get rid of the question of &quot;additional character&quot; nor the method for compute the loans.
France could change its position to become as progressive on this issue as it is on others.
Therefore, we are left with hope for the new Minister for the Environment, Mrs. Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancún next week.
A surprise announcement on France&#39;s fast start and on its vision of &quot;additional character&quot; and the use of loans would help to improve the level of international confidence necessary to advance the negotiations.
Warning about pesticides ingested by children
A 10-year-old boy ingests 81 different chemical substances in one day, according to a study published Wednesday by the Générations Futures association (the old movement for the rights and respect of future generations).
The association, which warns that its results &quot;do not have significant statistical value taking into account the limited number of samples analysed, but are illustrative of the problems dealt with&quot;, purchased in supermarkets in the Oise and Paris between July and September the foods that are usually consume a child of about ten years in four meals and a snack a day.
These model meals, which adhere to official recommendations (five parts fresh fruit and vegetables, three parts dairy, and 1.5 liters of water per day), as well as sweets, were tested in laboratories for chemicals. , pesticides, heavy metals and other contaminants.
The balance of the plate is overwhelming: 81 chemical substances, of which 42 classified as possible or probable carcinogens and five substances classified as sure carcinogens, as well as 37 substances capable of acting as endocrine disruptors (EP), according to studies by various institutions such as the International Agency for Research on Cancer.
&quot;Although legal limits are not exceeded for individual chemicals in virtually all cases, our study clearly shows that consumer exposure to potentially carcinogenic contaminants and/or PE is of concern,&quot; indicates the association.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible carcinogenic residues and three considered safe carcinogens, as well as about twenty residues that can harm the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, intended as a school snack, contains traces of six chemicals, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same applies to Kenyan green beans, included in the meal, in which the study has detected traces of a powerful insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, the Russian steak, the canned tuna, and even the loaf of bread or gum were laced with pesticides and other chemicals.
In tap water, analyzes revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
At dinner, the salmon slice was the most &quot;nutritious&quot; with 34 chemical residues detected and even the analysis of the plastic plate used to microwave the food was not completely clean.
The ultimate risk that these &quot;contaminant cocktails&quot; pose to the consumer &quot;is probably underestimated,&quot; the study says.
The Alliance Europe Ecology-Les Verts (EE-LV), for its part, has proposed &quot;in view of the seriousness of the situation&quot; to apply a moratorium on the use of pesticides to curb &quot;the increase in diseases associated with civilization&quot;.
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EASA) indicated the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in the fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, of which 76 in cereals.
